thamerica/usa/11829434/Virginia-news-shooting-the-unanswered-questions.html|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=September 1, 2015|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Vester Flanagan Bought Gun Legally From Virginia Dealer, Officials Say|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/virginia-tv-shooting/vester-flanagan-bought-gun-legally-virginia-dealer-officials-say-n417136|author=Pete Williams|author2=Andrew Blankstein|author3=Tom Winter|website=NBC News|publisher=NBC News Group, LLC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 28, 2015|author-link=Pete Williams (journalist)}}</ref>\n| numparts    = <!-- or | numpart     = -->\n| dfens       = <!-- or | dfen        = -->\n| motive      = Perceived workplace animosity, supposed revenge for the [[Charleston church shooting]]<ref name=cnn.virginia.shooting>{{cite news|title=Police: Bryce Williams fatally shoots self after killing journalists on air|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/26/us/virginia-shooting-wdbj/|author=Eliott C. McLaughlin|author2=Catherine E. Shoichet|website=CNN|publisher=Time Warner|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n| website     = <!-- URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\nNews reporter Alison Parker and photojournalist Adam Ward were employees of CBS affiliate [[WDBJ]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia]] who were fatally shot on August 26, 2015, while conducting a live television interview near [[Smith Mountain Lake]] in [[Moneta, Virginia|Moneta]]. They were interviewing Vicki Gardner, executive director of the local chamber of commerce, when all three were attacked by a gunman. Parker, age 24, and Ward, age 27, died at the scene, while Gardner survived.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two WDBJ7 employees killed in attack at Bridgewater Plaza|url=http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/law-enforcement-investigating-incident-at-bridgewater-plaza/34923086|author=Web Staff|website=[[WDBJ]]|publisher=Schurz Communications|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826131524/http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/law-enforcement-investigating-incident-at-bridgewater-plaza/34923086|archivedate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> The gunman was 41-year-old Vester Lee Flanagan II, also known by the professional pseudonym of Bryce Williams, a former reporter at WDBJ. The station fired him for disruptive conduct in 2013.<ref name=\"nytimes_20150826\">{{cite news|title=Virginia TV Reporter and Photographer Shot During Live Broadcast|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/us/wdbj7-virginia-journalists-shot-during-live-broadcast.html|first=Katie|last=Rogers|author2=Alan Blinder| newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> After a five-hour manhunt, Flanagan shot himself during a car chase with police officers and died later at a hospital.<ref name=\"usat_Susp\">{{cite web|title=Suspect in on-air murder of journalists kills himself|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/08/26/reports-two-dead-virginia-shooting-live-tv/32391633/|first=John|last=Bacon|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=USAToday.Angered/><ref name=ShotHimself>{{Cite web|title = WDBJ Shooting Suspect Shot Himself, Died in Hospital|url = http://www.whsv.com/home/headlines/Roanoke-News-Crew-Involved-in-Shooting-Incident-322939771.html|website = WHSV 3|accessdate = October 25, 2015|last = Williamson|first = Jeff|date = August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n\n===Murders===\nParker and Ward were conducting a live interview with Gardner at Bridgewater Plaza in Moneta about upcoming events for the 50th anniversary of [[Smith Mountain Lake]], {{convert|26|mi}} southeast of Roanoke. The shooting occurred at 6:46&nbsp;a.m. Eastern Time in the middle of the segment, which was broadcast on WDBJ's morning news program ''Mornin{{'}}''. Video of the incident showed Parker conducting the interview when at least eight gunshots were heard, followed by screams. Ward's camera fell to the ground, briefly capturing the image of Flanagan holding a [[Glock|Glock 19]] 9mm pistol.<ref name=SunTimes.Obtained/><ref name=Telegraph.Unanswered/>\n\nWDBJ production master control operators then switched back to ''Mornin{{'}}'' anchor Kimberly McBroom at the station's news studio, seemingly confused by what had just happened. She later said that she believed the noises could have been a car backfiring or shots being fired in the background.<ref>{{cite news|title=News anchor thought car backfired when gunman shot colleagues on air|url=http://www.9news.com.au/world/2015/08/27/15/03/news-anchor-thought-car-backfired-after-colleagues-murdered-on-air|website=Nine News|publisher=Nine Entertainment Co.|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Immediate aftermath===\nParker and Ward died at the scene. Gardner was also shot, but she survived following surgery at [[Carilion Roanoke Memorial Hospital]].<ref>\n*{{Cite web|title = Family of Vicki Gardner issues statement: 'We are grateful'|url = http://wtvr.com/2015/08/28/family-of-vicki-gardner-issues-statement-we-are-grateful/|website = WTVR.com|accessdate = August 30, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Reporter and cameraman killed during live broadcast|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/reporter-and-cameraman-killed-during-live-broadcast|first=Anna|last=Brand|website=MSNBC|publisher=NBC News|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Fired reporter kills 2 former co-workers on live TV|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/379b43ac8db44392a594ee48ed889a84/manager-2-virginia-tv-station-workers-fatally-shot-air|first=Steve|last=Helber|author2=Pam Ramsey|author3=Jonathan Drew|agency=Associated Press|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Vicki Gardner declared 'poster child' for bullet wound recovery at CRMH|url=http://wsls.com/2015/08/31/vicki-gardner-declared-poster-child-for-bullet-wound-recovery-at-crmh/|work=WSLS10|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> According to the state medical examiner's office, Parker died from gunshot wounds to her head and chest, while Ward died from shots to his head and torso.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia shootings: Slain TV journalists shot both in head and body|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/virginia-shootings-slain-tv-journalists-shot-both-in-head-and-body-1.3207446|website=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref> Gardner was shot in the back after she curled into a fetal position in an attempt to play dead.<ref name=\"nyt_gardner\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2015/10/07/tv-shooting-survivor-vicki-gardner-intv-ac-cutdown.cnn|title=WDBJ shooting survivor: 'I played dead'|work=CNN|date=October 7, 2015|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> A total of 15 shots were fired.<ref name=Heavy.Facts>{{cite web|title=Vester Lee Flanagan: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|url=http://heavy.com/news/2015/08/lester-lee-flanagan-flanighan-flanigan-wdbj-tv-disgruntled-employee-virginia-shooting-suspect-cameraman-photos-video-chase-gun-gunman-arrested/|first=Tom|last=Cleary|website=heavy.com|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nStaff in the WDBJ newsroom  reviewed video of the incident from Ward's fallen camera and identified Flanagan as the likely gunman. They alerted general manager Jeffrey Marks, who passed the information to the county sheriff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia TV Shooting: Chilling Image Alerted Station to Killer Vester Flanagan|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/virginia-tv-shooting/virginia-tv-shooting-chilling-image-alerted-station-killer-vester-flanagan-n416826|first=Erin|last=McClam|website=NBC News|publisher=NBC News Group, LLC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan faxed ABC News at 8:23&nbsp;a.m. and then phoned shortly after 10:00&nbsp;a.m., making a confession.<ref name=Jack/> During the ensuing manhunt, authorities tracked Flanagan's cell phone to locate him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia gunman details grievances in lengthy 'suicide note,' references Charleston church shooting|url=http://fox8.com/2015/08/26/virginia-gunman-details-grievances-in-lengthy-suicide-note-references-charleston-church-shooting/|agency=[[CNN]]wire|website=WJW|publisher=Tribune Broadcasting|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlanagan abandoned his [[Ford Mustang]] at the [[Roanoke\u2013Blacksburg Regional Airport]] and drove a rented [[Chevrolet Sonic]] north on [[I-81]], then east on [[I-66]]. An automated license plate reader in a Virginia state trooper's car identified the rented Sonic at 11:20&nbsp;a.m. The trooper called for backup and attempted to initiate a traffic stop, but Flanagan sped away. His car ran off the side of the road and struck an embankment near [[Markham, Fauquier County, Virginia|Markham]] after a pursuit of less than two miles.<ref name=markham>{{cite news|title=TV murder suspect fatally shoots himself in Fauquier|url=http://www.fauquiernow.com/index.php/fauquier_news/article/fauquier-tv-murder-suspect-kills-himself-in-fauquier-2015|work=Fauquier Now|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> He was found inside the car with gunshot wounds<ref name=\"USAToday.Angered\" /> which were apparently self-inflicted while he was driving.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suspect in Virginia Shooting of News Team Commits Suicide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/us/wdbj7-virginia-journalists-shot-during-live-broadcast.html?_r=0|first=Hawes|last=Spencer|author2=Katie Rogers|author3=Alan Blinder|author4=Richard P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He was airlifted to [[Inova Fairfax Hospital]] in [[Falls Church, Virginia|Falls Church]], where he was declared dead at 1:26&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=ShotHimself/><ref>{{cite news|title=Suspect in On-Air Shooting Dies From Self-Inflicted Wound|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/suspect-air-shooting-dead-inflicted-wound/story?id=33327920|first=Meghan|last=Keneally|website=ABC News|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=WPost.Slaying>{{cite news|title=Suspect in slaying of two TV station employees in SW Virginia shoots himself and dies|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2015/08/26/tv-camera-crew-caught-in-active-shooter-situation-in-southwest-virginia/|first=Dana|last=Hedgpeth|author2=Justin Jouvenal|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\n[[File:Alison Parker and Adam Ward.jpg|thumb|Parker and Ward, from WDBJ7's [[Twitter]] account]]\n'''Alison Bailey Parker'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heralddemocrat.com/article/20150828/NEWS/308289872|title=Austin College alumni and staff mourn slain newscaster|publisher=}}</ref> (August 19, 1991 \u2013 August 26, 2015) grew up in [[Martinsville, Virginia]] and attended [[Patrick Henry Community College]] and [[James Madison University]]. She interned at WDBJ in 2012, worked as a general assignment news reporter at ABC affiliate [[WCTI-TV]] in [[New Bern, North Carolina]] from December 2012 until May 2014,<ref>{{cite web|title=Former WCTI reporter killed during TV live shot|url=http://www.wcti12.com/news/former-wcti-reporter-killed-during-tv-live-shot/34924588|first=Jaime|last=McCutcheon|website=[[WCTI-TV]]|publisher=[[Bonten Media Group]]|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826180157/http://www.wcti12.com/news/former-wcti-reporter-killed-during-tv-live-shot/34924588|archivedate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> and then was hired by WDBJ in 2014 as a correspondent for ''Mornin{{'}}''.<ref name=cnn.virginia.shooting/><ref>{{cite web|title=A look at the lives of WDBJ7's Alison Parker and Adam Ward|url=http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/a-look-at-the-lives-of-wdbj7s-alison-parker-and-adam-ward/34929588|first=Joe|last=Dashiell|website=WDBJ|publisher=Schurz Communications|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828050405/http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/a-look-at-the-lives-of-wdbj7s-alison-parker-and-adam-ward/34929588|archivedate=August 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Adam Laing Ward'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2015/08/26/adam-ward-wdbj7-photojournalist/32411325/|title=WDBJ7 TV: Adam Ward was a 'fine photojournalist'|website=USA TODAY}}</ref> (May 10, 1988 \u2013 August 26, 2015) grew up in [[Salem, Virginia]] and graduated from [[Virginia Tech]] with a degree in communications and media studies in 2011. He had worked at the station since July 2011 as a videographer, as well as an occasional sports reporter.<ref>{{cite web|title=WDBJ reporter Alison Parker, photographer Adam Ward hailed by colleagues, friends|url=http://wtvr.com/2015/08/26/wdbj-reporter-alison-parker-photographer-adam-ward-hailed-by-colleagues-friends/|website=WTVR-TV|publisher=Tribune Broadcasting|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Andy Parker criticizes Senators\">{{cite news|title=WDBJ reporter's father criticizes senators for not calling family|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/28/politics/alison-parker-shooting-wdbj-father-andy-parker-senators/|first=Eugene|last=Scott|author2=Ted Barrett|website=CNN|publisher=Time Warner|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVicki Gardner is originally from [[Union Springs, New York]] and has been the executive director of the Smith Mountain Lake Regional Chamber of Commerce since 2002.<ref name=WPost.Head>{{cite web|title=Shooting victim Vicki Gardner is head of local chamber of commerce|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/third-victim-in-virginia-shooting-is-head-of-local-chamber-of-commerce/2015/08/26/1ad878a4-4c03-11e5-bfb9-9736d04fc8e4_story.html|first=Antonio|last=Olivo|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> She underwent surgery in which her kidney and part of her colon were removed<ref name=\"nyt_gardner\" /> and was released from the hospital on September 8, 2015.<ref name=\"nyt_gardner\">{{cite web|first=Christine|last=Hauser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/09/us/woman-injured-in-virginia-tv-shooting-is-out-of-the-hospital.html|title=Woman Injured in Virginia TV Shooting Is Out of the Hospital|work=The New York Times|date=September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Vester Lee Flanagan\n|image       = <!--do not add image per FFD-->\n|birth_name  = Vester Lee Flanagan II\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1973|10|8}}<ref name=\"CBI\">{{cite web|author=California Birth Index |title=Vester L Flanagan, Born 10/08/1973 in California|url=http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/vester_l_flanagan_born_1973_11921659|publisher=California Birth Index|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Oakland, California]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|2015|8|26|1973|10|8}} \n|death_place = [[Falls Church, Virginia]], U.S.\n|death_cause = Self-inflicted gunshot wounds\n|residence   = [[Roanoke, Virginia]], U.S.\n|nationality = American\n|occupation  = Television news journalist; former model\n|education   = [[San Francisco State University]]\n|other_names = Bryce Williams\n}}\n\n===Personal background===\nVester Lee Flanagan II (October 8, 1973 \u2013 August 26, 2015) was known professionally as Bryce Williams and was a native of [[Oakland, California]]. His family were [[Jehovah's Witnesses]].<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web |last1=Matt Pearce, Lee Romney and Natalie Schachar |title=Suspect in killing of Virginia TV crew said he was 'just waiting to go BOOM' |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-virginia-tv-station-workers-fatally-shot-on-air-20150826-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=August 26, 2019 |ref=latimes |date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He graduated from [[Skyline High School (Oakland, California)|Skyline High School]] and attended [[San Francisco State University]], earning a degree in radio and television in 1995. He interned at CBS affiliate [[KPIX-TV|KPIX]] in [[San Francisco]] in 1993, eventually working there as a production assistant and weekend news writer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suspected killer in Virginia slayings had Bay Area ties|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Suspected-killer-in-Virginia-slayings-of-6466587.php|first=Evan|last=Sernoffsky|author2=Kurtis Alexander|author3=Jenna Lyons|author4=Rachel Swan|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|publisher=Hearst Corporation|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He had been a small-time actor and model before beginning his career in journalism.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia shooter Vester Lee Flanagan is former model, 'high paid companion'; had sued news station for discrimination|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/gunman-posts-video-showing-fatal-shooting-tv-reporter-article-1.2337769|first=Melissa|last=Chan|newspaper=New York Daily News|publisher=Daily News, L.P.|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlanagan worked as a general assignment news reporter at CBS affiliate [[WTOC-TV]] in [[Savannah, Georgia]] from February 1997 to March 1999.<ref name=CBS.Blamed>{{cite web|title=Report: Suspect in deadly on-air attack blamed Charleston shooting|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/wdbj-shootig-suspect-vester-lee-flanagan-suspect-in-deadly-virginia-television-shooting-of-alison|website=CBS News|publisher=CBS Interactive|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He worked as a reporter for NBC affiliate [[WTWC-TV]] in [[Tallahassee, Florida]] between March 1999 and March 2000. He later reported to news director Don Shafer that co-workers were making offensive comments about his sexual orientation. In an interview with the ''Daily Mail'', former WTWC sports reporter Dave Leval said that Flanagan verbally abused two female staffers at the station on different occasions after they pointed out mistakes in his reporting, and several photographers tried to get out of working on stories to which Flanagan was assigned due to his \"diva\" behavior.<ref>\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiego6.com/news/local/SD6-News-Director-hired-and-fired-suspect-in-2000-in-FL-322971901.html#|title=SD6 News Director hired, fired WDBJ shooting suspect at FL station in 2000|last=Hood|first=Lindsay|date=August 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109210323/http://www.sandiego6.com/news/local/SD6-News-Director-hired-and-fired-suspect-in-2000-in-FL-322971901.html|archive-date=November 9, 2015|url-status=dead|publisher=Bay City Television/Grupo Televisa|agency=City News Service|first2=Laura|last2=Nguyen|website=XETV-TDT|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}\n*{{cite news|title=Former News Director: Roanoke Killer Would Get Into Physical Conflicts With Staff|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/ex-colleagues-of-virginia-gunman-say-many-tried-to-mentor-and-support-him/2015/08/28/07d2598e-4da5-11e5-84df-923b3ef1a64b_story.html|first=Kerry|last=Picket|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlanagan lost his job due to \"odd behavior\" in March 2000, and he filed a civil lawsuit against WTWC alleging racial discrimination, as he was African-American. The lawsuit was settled under unspecified terms in January 2001. WTWC's owner [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] had discontinued the station's news operations in November 2000 due to poor ratings and budget reductions.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Flanagan worked for CBS affiliate [[WNCT-TV]] in [[Greenville, North Carolina]] from 2002 to 2004.<ref name=CBS.Blamed/><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Here's What We Know About The Virginia Shooting Suspect|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/davidmack/heres-what-we-know-about-the-virginia-tv-shooter|first=David|last=Mack|website=BuzzFeed|publisher=BuzzFeed Inc.|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also found some work at ABC affiliate [[KMID (TV)|KMID]] in [[Midland, Texas]].<ref name=Heavy.Facts/>\n\n===Tenure at WDBJ===\nWDBJ announced on April 19, 2012 that they hired Flanagan as a multimedia journalist under the professional name Bryce Williams.<ref name=adweek1>{{cite web|title=WDBJ Adds Two Veteran Reporters|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/wdbj-adds-two-veteran-reporters/46832|first=Andrew|last=Gauthier|website=[[AdWeek|TVSpy]]|publisher=Mediabistro Holdings|date=April 19, 2012|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Documents relating to his time at WDBJ suggest that the station's management considered him an experienced reporter, but there were conflicts with other reporters and with photographers.<ref name=NYTimes.Turbulent>{{cite news|title=Documents Show Vester Lee Flanagan's Turbulent Tenure at TV Station Before Virginia Shooting|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/us/documents-show-virginia-shooting-suspects-turbulent-tenure-at-tv-station.html|first=Alan|last=Blinder|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Office memos from WDBJ showed that news director Dan Dennison ordered him to contact [[Health Advocate]] in July 2012 after receiving complaints that co-workers were \"feeling threatened or uncomfortable\" while working with him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia shootings: Gunman ordered to seek medical help|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-34070393|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> It is unclear whether he did so prior to his dismissal.<ref name=FOX.Inside>{{cite news|title=Inside Vester Lee Flanagan's life|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2015/08/27/inside-vester-lee-flanagan-life|website=Fox News|publisher=Fox News Network, LLC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWDBJ dismissed Flanagan on February 1, 2013 because of his volatile behavior. According to a former colleague, upon learning of his dismissal, Flanagan lashed out at news room staffers, resulting in the staffers being put in a room while police escorted him out of the building. Ward allegedly recorded Flanagan as he was escorted out, and the two men had a confrontation earlier that day. Flanagan allegedly threw a wooden cross at Dennison, saying, \"You need this.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Vester Flanagan told to seek medical help by Virginia TV station, say memos|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/aug/26/virginia-gunman-vester-flanagan-wdbj-2012-memos-medical-help|first=Lauren|last=Gambino|author2=Jon Swaine|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> WDBJ provided security to the staffers for a time after the incident and directed them to call the police if he ever returned to the station.<ref name=NYTimes.Turbulent/><ref>\n*{{cite news|title=Bryce Williams: A meticulous plan for a live televised murder|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/27/us/virginia-shooting-wdbj-bryce-williams-parker-adams/index.html|author1=Ben Brumfield|author2=Eliott C. McLaughlin|author3=Catherine E. Shoichet|website=CNN|publisher=Time Warner|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite web|title=Accused WDBJ Killer Shoots Self; Had Been Fired From Station in 2013|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/wdbj-shooter-was-a-known-problem/154167|first=Kevin|last=Eck|website=TVSpy|publisher=Mediabistro Holdings|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan filed an [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission|EEOC]] complaint against WDBJ, alleging racial discrimination, and he allegedly named Parker in it. The EEOC investigated, then dismissed the complaint as uncorroborated.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>\n*{{cite web|title=Virginia TV shooter posts chilling video|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2015/08/virginia_tv_shooter_posts_chil.html|first=Leada|last=Gore|newspaper=[[The Birmingham News]]|publisher=Advance Publications|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Vester Flanagan: Everything we know about the gunman who killed two WDBJ journalists on-air|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/police-hunt-former-news-anchor-vester-flanagan-in-the-killing-of-two-wbdj-journalists-10473200.html|first=Justin|last=Carissimo|newspaper=The Independent|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan wrote a suicide note in which he said that he killed both of his cats out of rage after the incident.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/28/us/vester-lee-flanagan-grievances-homicidal-explosion.html?referrer=&_r=1|date=August 27, 2015|work=The New York Times|title=A Life of Listing Grievances, and Then Virginia Gunman's Final Homicidal Explosion|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/vester-flanagan-virginia-news-crew-shooter-killed-two-cats-murders-366599|title=Vester Flanagan, Virginia News Crew Shooter, Killed Two Cats Before Murders|work=Newsweek|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}\n*{{Cite journal|title = Inside the Warped Mind of Vester Flanagan and Other Shooters|url = https://newrepublic.com/article/122669/injustice-collectors-how-understand-vester-flanagans-manifesto|journal = The New Republic|date = September 23, 2015|accessdate = October 5, 2015|author = Dave Cullen}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his dismissal, Flanagan got a job at a local [[UnitedHealth Group]] call center. He had a confrontation with a female employee who casually pointed out how quiet he was being, to which he responded aggressively, telling her to never talk to him again.<ref>{{cite news|title=On-air shooter threatened to make 'headlines,' showed anger|url=https://news.yahoo.com/air-killings-gripped-millions-social-media-storm-071552249.html|first=Adam|last=Geller|author2=Alan Suderman|website=Yahoo! News|publisher=Yahoo!|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> One of Flanagan's neighbors in his apartment complex described him as an arrogant person who acted rudely towards people around him. He was noted for sometimes throwing cat feces at the homes of neighbors with whom he had disputes.<ref name=FOX.Inside/>\n\n===Shooting and motives===\n{{tweet|name= Bryce Williams|username=bryce_williams7 |number=636556064285151232 |date=August 26, 2015 |text=Alison made racist comments|unverified =y|reference =<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schultz |first1=Marisa |last2=Rosario |first2=Frank |title=The comments that became a reporter's death sentence |url=https://nypost.com/2015/08/28/reporters-everyday-comments-deemed-racist-by-on-air-killer/ |accessdate=September 26, 2018 |work=[[New York Post]] |date=August 28, 2015}}</ref> }}\nFlanagan maintained accounts on [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] which were suspended after he was named as a suspect in the shooting. He repeated his claims of racial discrimination by WDBJ on both profiles, specifically naming Parker and Ward. He claimed that Parker had made a coded racist remark during her internship at WDBJ regarding a friend of Flanagan's, and that Ward had filed a complaint against him to WDBJ's human resources department after working with him on one occasion.<ref name=\"usatoday_anger\">{{cite news|title=Former co-workers say Vester Flanagan had problems with work, anger, racism|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/08/28/former-co-workers-say-vester-flanagan-had-problems-work-anger-racism/71339660/|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 29, 2015|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt 11:14&nbsp;a.m. on the day of the shooting, Flanagan uploaded a 56-second phone camera video to his Twitter and Facebook accounts before they were suspended, shot from a first-person perspective of the incident.<ref>\n*{{cite news|title=Chilling video shows gunman's perspective of on-air shooting in Virginia|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/08/26/two-dead-virginia-shooting-live-tv-social-media/32401101/|first=Emily|last=Brown|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=The Latest: Police had contact with killer after firing|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/the-latest-on-tv-shooting-husband-overjoyed-wife-is-alive/2015/08/27/064da9b0-4d23-11e5-80c2-106ea7fb80d4_story.html|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> The video shows him walking up to the scene of the interview and brandishing a handgun for approximately 15 seconds without Ward, Parker, or Gardner noticing; Gardner later said that she had been blinded by the television lighting.<ref name=\"gardner\">{{cite news|title=Virginia shooting: injured woman says she did not see gunman before he fired|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/aug/29/virginia-tv-news-shooting-vicki-gardner-injured-woman|newspaper=The Guardian|date=August 29, 2015|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref> He mutters \"bitch\" while pointing the weapon at Parker, and lowers the gun before raising it again and opening fire directly at her. Parker flinches and screams before attempting to escape the attack, and the light of Ward's camera is seen quickly dropping before Flanagan pulls the camera away and shuts it off.<ref name=NYDailyNews.Broadcast/><ref>\n*{{cite web|title=Alleged Newscast Gunman Shoots Self After Posting Vid Of Shooting|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/vester-flanagan-tweets-shooting|first=Caitlin|last=McNeal|website=[[Talking Points Memo]]|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Reporter, photographer shot to death on air in Virginia; suspect dies at hospital|url=http://my.chicagotribune.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-84289393/|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Ex-coworker shoots, kills news crew on live TV in Virginia|url=http://abc7chicago.com/news/ex-coworker-kills-virginia-news-crew-on-live-tv-/958110/|author=Chuck Goudie|author2=Ross Weidner|author3=Ann Pistone|author4=Christine Tressel|author5=Barbara Markoff|website=WLS-TV|publisher=ABC Owned Television Stations|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nABC News received a 23-page fax at 8:26&nbsp;a.m. allegedly sent by Flanagan<ref>{{cite news|title=Suspect in On-Air Virginia Shooting Identified|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/tv-reporter-camerman-killed-gunman-opens-fire-virginia/story?id=33327920|author=Meghan Keneally via Good Morning America|website=ABC News|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> entitled \"Suicide Note for Friend & Family\". He described his grievances over what he alleged to be racial discrimination and sexual harassment committed by black men and white women in his workplace, believing that he was targeted because he was a homosexual black man.<ref name=USAToday.Angered>{{cite news|title=Disturbed' Va. gunman angered by Charleston shootings|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/08/26/alleged-va-shooter-had-history-workplace-racism-complaints/32404967/|first=Doug|last=Stanglin|author2=Tyler Pager|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Jack>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/beta/US/shooting-alleged-gunman-details-grievances-suicide-notes/story?id=33336339|title=After Shooting, Alleged Gunman Details Grievances in 'Suicide Notes'|first=Pierre|last=Thomas|author2=Jack Cloherty|author3=Jack Date|author4=Mike Levine|website=ABC News|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=reuters_powder_keg>{{cite news|title=Virginia TV journalists killed by suspect with 'powder keg' of anger|url=https://news.yahoo.com/two-virginia-television-journalists-fatally-shot-air-attack-130244085.html|first=Gary|last=Robertson|agency=[[Reuters]]|website=Yahoo! News|publisher=Yahoo!|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan claimed to have been provoked by the [[Charleston church shooting]] two months before and made threatening comments about [[Dylann Roof]], the perpetrator of that crime.<ref name=NYDailyNews.Broadcast>{{cite news |title=TV news reporter, cameraman are fatally shot during live broadcast in Virginia; suspected shooter posts video of attack, then kills himself |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/shot-live-tv-news-broadcast-virginia-article-1.2337586 |first=Jason |last=Silverstein |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=August 26, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He described the church shooting as a \"tipping point\", saying that his anger had been \"building steadily\" and describing himself as \"a human powder keg\u2026 just waiting to go BOOM\".<ref name=USAToday.Angered /> A spokesman for the Franklin County Sheriff's Office said that Flanagan \"very closely identified\" with \"individuals who have committed domestic acts of violence and mass murder, as well as the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001 attacks]] on the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Vester Flanagan 'very closely identified' with foreign, domestic terrorists: Police|url=http://www.cbs12.com/news/top-stories/stories/vester-flanagan-very-closely-identified-foreign-domestic-terrorists-police-28780.shtml|work=CBS12.com|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> He said that [[Jehovah]] had told him to act and expressed an admiration for [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]], who perpetrated the 1999 [[Columbine High School massacre]]; and [[Seung-Hui Cho]], the perpetrator of the 2007 [[Virginia Tech shooting]].<ref name=Jack/><ref>{{cite news|title=Vester Lee Flanagan II, aka Bryce Williams, Named as Suspect in Live TV Shooting in Virginia|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/vester-lee-flanagan-ii-named-suspect-live-tv-shootings-virginia-n416331|first=Erin|last=McClam|website=NBC News|publisher=NBC News|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan said in the note, \"Yeah I'm all fucked up in the head.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=What we know so far about Vester Lee Flanagan, the man who shot dead two journalists on TV|url=http://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/life/current-affairs/what-we-know-so-far-about-vester-lee-flanagan-man-who-shot-dead-two-journalists-tv/|website=bailiwickexpress.com|accessdate=September 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter Flanagan's death, officers searched his rental car and found various items, including a [[Glock]] pistol with several [[Magazine (firearms)|magazines]] and ammunition, a cell phone, letters, notes, a \"to-do\" list, a suitcase containing three license plates, and several disguises, including a wig.<ref name=FOX.Inside/><ref name=WPost.Prepared>{{cite news|title=In Roanoke shooter's car, signs he was prepared to remain on the run|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/journalists-cope-a-day-after-fatal-shooting-of-colleagues-in-roanoke/2015/08/27/34c5f40e-4cbb-11e5-bfb9-9736d04fc8e4_story.html|first=Justin|last=Jouvenal|author2=Julie Zauzmer|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===Reactions===\nPresident [[Barack Obama]] said that he was heartbroken over the murders,<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama On Virginia Shooting: 'It Breaks My Heart'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/obama-virginia-shooting_55de347fe4b0e7117ba8c664|first=Paige|last=Lavender|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=AOL|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> and Virginia Governor [[Terry McAuliffe]] said on Twitter that he also was heartbroken over the shooting, and he reasserted his support for gun control.<ref name=WPost.Slaying/> He later made calls for tougher gun laws in the state and blamed the state legislature for failing to pass a package of gun control measures that he had proposed earlier in January.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gov. Terry McAuliffe Calls For Tougher Gun Laws After Virginia Shooting|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/terry-mcauliffe-gun-control-virginia-shooting_55ddd4fbe4b0a40aa3acea2f|first=Kim|last=Bellware|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=AOL|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> His remarks drew criticism from Republicans, who said that he was politicizing the tragedy.<ref name=WPost.Prepared/> Virginia Senator [[Mark Warner]] gave his condolences to Parker and Ward's families, as well as to WDBJ and the first responders involved.<ref name=WPost.Slaying/>\n\nParker's father Andy Parker said that he would become an advocate on the issue of gun violence prevention, comparing it to [[John Walsh (television host)|John Walsh]]'s advocacy of crime prevention, and he said that he would speak with politicians and news outlets to address issues of mental health and improving care for those with mental illnesses. He had run as a Democratic candidate for the Virginia House of Delegates in 2007 but was not elected, and he urged politicians to strengthen laws against gun violence. His comments were made against pressure from the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA), whom he criticized for preventing Senators and Representatives from passing such legislation in the past. He criticized Virginia Senators [[Tim Kaine]], who criticized the NRA for blocking efforts by the Virginia General Assembly and Congress to tighten background checks for gun purchases, and Mark Warner for not directly contacting his family following the announcement that his daughter was one of the victims.<ref name=\"Andy Parker criticizes Senators\"/><ref name=\"HuffPo-CTV\">\n*{{cite news|title=Slain Reporter's Father Fears For His Safety As He Takes Up Gun Control Activism|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/andy-parker-gun-control-alison-parker_55e0af1be4b0b7a96338e827|first=Amanda|last=Terkel|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=AOL|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Slain journalist's father says he'll push for stricter gun laws in U.S.|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/slain-journalist-s-father-says-he-ll-push-for-stricter-gun-laws-in-u-s-1.2536192|first=Emily|last=Chan|website=[[CTV News]]|publisher=[[Bell Media]]|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nStaff members for Senator Kaine explained that Kaine had not contacted the victims' families at the time \"out of respect for their space and privacy during this difficult time of grieving\". The same reasoning was cited by Mark Warner on August 29, who said he did not immediately contact Parker's family out of respect to the family's privacy \"at a time of unimaginable grief\".<ref name=\"Andy Parker criticizes Senators\"/><ref name=\"HuffPo-CTV\"/>\n\nThe shooting led Alison Parker's boyfriend [[Chris Hurst (Virginia politician)|Chris Hurst]] to successfully run for a seat in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] with a priority to pass gun safety legislation.<ref name=\"Graun\">[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/feb/22/wdbj-shooting-chris-hurst-virginia-alison-parker-joseph-yost Boyfriend of reporter killed on live TV aims to unseat NRA-endorsed lawmaker], by Lois Beckett, at ''[[the Guardian]]''; published February 22, 2017. Retrieved November 8, 2017</ref>\n\n===Media response===\nIn the immediate wake of the shooting, various media productions were either delayed or pulled from television outlets. The first-season finale of the series ''[[Mr. Robot (TV series)|Mr. Robot]]'' was postponed one week from its originally scheduled air date (the day of the murders) because the episode included a scene with similarities to the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/08/26/usa-mr-robot-finale-postponed-virginia-live-tv-shooting/32430401/|title='Mr. Robot' finale delayed after Va. murders|first=Bill|last=Keveney|date=August 27, 2015|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> [[IFC (U.S. TV network)|IFC]] delayed airing an episode of its satirical series ''[[Documentary Now!]]'' which centered on two journalists who are killed on-camera as they track down a Mexican drug cartel leader.<ref>\n*{{cite web|title=IFC Delays 'Documentary Now' Episode After News Team's On-Air Shooting|url=http://deadline.com/2015/08/documentary-delayed-by-ifc-now-following-virginia-shooting-1201508476/|first=Erik|last=Pedersen|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}\n*{{cite web|title=IFC's 'Documentary Now!' Delays Episode Due to Virginia Shooting|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/documentary-now-wdbj-shooting-virginia-1201580024/|first=Whitney|last=Friedlander|website=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> [[Warner Records|Warner Bros. Records]] decided to pull a television commercial for [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]'s album ''[[Immortalized (Disturbed album)|Immortalized]]'', as it depicted an incident similar to the killings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disturbed Album Ad Pulled After Eerie Parallels to On-Air Shooting|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/disturbed-album-ad-pulled-after-eerie-parallels-to-127737096001.html|author=Billy Johnson Jr.|website=Yahoo! Music|publisher=Yahoo!|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWriting about news coverage of the incident, [[ThinkProgress]] noted, \"There isn\u2019t broad consensus about how to handle this type of coverage.\"<ref name=thinkprogress/> Users of [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] criticized the sites' autoplay option, which allowed opted-in viewers to see graphic images of the shooting without warning.<ref>\n*{{cite news|title=Facebook and Twitter users complain over Virginia shooting videos autoplay|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/aug/27/facebook-twitter-users-complain-virginia-shooting-videos-autoplay|first=Samuel|last=Gibbs|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Virginia murders show ugly side of autoplay|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/08/26/technology/autoplay-twitter-facebook-virginia-shooter/|author=Sara Ashley O'Brien|website=CNN Money|publisher=Time Warner|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> The ''New York Post'', the ''New York Daily News'', and British tabloids ''The Daily Mirror'' and ''The Sun'' were criticized for their decision to publish still frames from Flanagan's phone video of the murders on their front pages.<ref>\n*{{cite news|title='New York Daily News' cover causes outrage over graphic images of slain journalist|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2015/08/27/new-york-daily-news-virginia-reporters-murdered-live-tv-newspaper-cover/32469823/|first=Mary|last=Bowerman|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Withnall |date=August 27, 2015 |title=Virginia shooting: New York Daily News and other newspapers spark outrage with front pages 'letting killer tell the story' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/virginia-shooting-new-york-daily-news-and-other-newspapers-spark-outrage-with-front-pages-letting-killer-tell-the-story-10474159.html |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> ''ABC World News Tonight'' did not show any part of Flanagan's video, ''NBC Nightly News'' broadcast a still frame, and ''CBS Evening News'' showed a 25-second segment of the video.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Ariens |date=August 27, 2015 |title=Of Evening Broadcasts, Only CBS Showed Gunman's Video of Deadly Shooting |url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/only-cbs-news-showed-gunmans-video-of-deadly-shooting/270539 |website=TVNewser |publisher=Mediabistro Holdings |accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> CNN aired the footage once every hour on the day of the shooting.<ref name=thinkprogress>{{cite web |first=Tara |last=Culp-Ressler |date=August 26, 2015 |title=The Media's Ethical Dilemma About How To Handle Footage Of People Shot On Live TV |url=https://thinkprogress.org/the-medias-ethical-dilemma-about-how-to-handle-footage-of-people-shot-on-live-tv-db2c3943c04d |website=ThinkProgress |accessdate=December 15, 2016 }}</ref> The gun control lobbying group [[Everytown for Gun Safety]] shared the broadcast video with a three-second discretionary warning, despite WDBJ's plea on Twitter not to \"share or post the video\".<ref name=Kaufman>{{cite news |first=Alexander C. |last=Kaufman |date=August 26, 2015 |title=A Major Gun Control Group Wants You to Watch the Virginia Shooting Video |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/gun-control-virginia-shooting_us_55de1c09e4b0a40aa3ad46d2 |website=The Huffington Post |accessdate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nChristine Courtois chairs the [[American Psychological Association]]'s post-traumatic stress disorder guidelines development panel, and she warned that anyone watching the footage was likely to be upset, possibly leading to acute stress disorder.<ref>{{cite news|title=The murders that rocked breakfast television|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-34047643|first=Vanessa|last=Barford|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> ''The Guardian'' journalist [[Catherine Bennett (journalist)|Catherine Bennett]] criticized the media's use of frame shots and footage as \"helping Flanagan achieve his vanity script.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Catherine |last=Bennett |date=August 29, 2015 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/30/alison-parker-adam-ward-vester-flanagan-tv-shooting |title=Nobody had to see Alison Parker's terror as she faced death |website=The Guardian |accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref> ''Ebony'' writer [[Jamilah Lemieux]]<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Jamilah |last=Lemieux |date=August 27, 2015 |title=[WDBJ TRAGEDY] Death Videos, Grief and Complicated Emotions |url=http://www.ebony.com/news-views/wdbj-tragedy-death-videos-grief-and-complicated-emotions-543 |magazine=Ebony |accessdate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref> and Dexter Thomas of the ''Los Angeles Times''<ref>{{cite web |first=Dexter |last=Thomas |title=Are we afraid to watch white people dying? |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-are-we-afraid-to-watch-white-people-dying-20150826-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 13, 2016 |date=August 27, 2015 }}</ref> wrote that the American mainstream media were too selective about rebroadcasting the footage of Parker and Ward's deaths to white audiences but have frequently showed content of many black people being killed. ''Los Angeles Times'' writer [[Mary McNamara]] wrote that not watching the graphic footage to prevent the fulfillment of \"a killer's wish is not just absurd it's agreeing to adopt a murderer's way of thinking.\" She said that people should watch the footage, not for entertainment, but to realize how brutal the murders were.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mary |last=McNamara |date=August 26, 2015 |title=If we watch the Virginia TV shooting is the suspected shooter 'winning'? |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-critics-notebook-virginia-shooting-20150827-53-column.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 15, 2016 }}</ref> ''New York Daily News'' writer Linda Stasi said that media criticism of showing footage contradicted frequent media decisions to publish other violent content.<ref>{{cite web |first=Linda |last=Stasi |date=August 29, 2015 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/stasi-time-focus-evil-not-media-article-1.2341740 |title=It's time to focus on the evil, not the media |website=New York Daily News |accessdate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Virginia State Police ordered BBC journalists to delete the station's copy of the video of Flanagan crashing his car during the police chase before he committed suicide.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kierran |last=Petersen |date=August 26, 2015 |title=Update: Virginia police order BBC journalists to delete footage of suspected shooter's crash |url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-08-26/virginia-police-order-bbc-journalists-delete-footage-suspected-shooters-crash |website=PRI |accessdate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Battling online material ===\nIn a sworn Congressional Testimony in July 2019, Alison's father Andy Parker credited the [[HONR Network]] in assisting him to combat online offensive material and hoaxes spread after the tragedy, saying \"the HONR Network who worked long hours flagging videos so that I was spared. When finding offensive content, HONR volunteers would click the report button below each video and check the appropriate box explaining how the video violates [[YouTube]]'s Community Guidelines. Although hundreds of videos have been taken down due to their diligence, they are often stymied even with an enforceable copyright.\"<ref name=\"senate\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Parker%20Testimony1.pdf|title=Andy Parker Congressional Testimony|last=Parker|first=Andy|date=July 16, 2019|website=US Federal Judiciary Committee|language=en-us|format=PDF|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2019.10.27-051837/https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Parker%20Testimony1.pdf|archive-date=2019-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-sandy-hook-memorial-charities-htmlstory.html|title=Foundations Honor Sandy Hook Victims Six Years Later|last=Ormseth|first=Matthew|date=December 14, 2018|work=courant.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402204355/https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-sandy-hook-memorial-charities-htmlstory.html|archive-date=2019-04-02|publisher=Hartford Courant Media Group}}</ref> He also added \"I have engaged in direct communications with [[Google]] regarding the proliferation of these videos, but while they profess a desire to help, in reality they do nothing... [I met with] Google Director of Global Human Rights regarding specific content and our attempts to have it removed. Their response was \u201cWe\u2019re really trying\u201d. Since that meeting, there has been nothing but silence. Thanks to [[Section 230]], Google has complete immunity and therefore no incentive to respond.\"<ref name=senate /> On February 20, 2020, Andy Parker filed a complaint to the [[Federal Trade Commission]] alleging that YouTube had failed to enforce its own [[Terms of Service]] by keeping certain videos of the shooting on its website.<ref>{{cite web |last=Reichert |first=Corinne |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/youtube-faces-ftc-complaint-after-failing-to-take-down-videos-of-journalists-murder/|title=YouTube faces FTC complaint after failing to take down videos of journalist's murder |publisher=CNET |date=February 20, 2020 |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Virginia}}\n* [[Capital Gazette shooting]]\n* [[Christine Chubbuck]], a television news reporter and the first person to commit suicide on live television in 1974\n* [[Crime in Virginia]]\n* [[R. Budd Dwyer]], the former state treasurer of Pennsylvania who shot himself on live television in 1987\n* [[List of journalists killed in the United States]]\n* [[Workplace aggression]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Alison}}\n[[Category:2015 in American television]]\n[[Category:2015 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:2015 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2015]]\n[[Category:August 2015 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bedford County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Filmed killings]]\n[[Category:Journalists killed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder\u2013suicides in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence against European Americans]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence in the United States]]\n[[Category:Racism in television]]\n[[Category:Workplace violence]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Adam Ward|the Texas murderer|Adam Kelly Ward}}\n{{use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|2015 double-murder in the United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}} \n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Murders of Alison Parker and Adam Ward\n| partof      =\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| map         = {{Location map|USA Virginia#USA\n|float      = center\n|relief     = 1\n|label      = Moneta\n|lat        = 37.14330\n|long       = -79.67027\n|caption    = \n|marksize   = 5\n|border     = infobox\n|width      = 260\n}}\n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     =\n| map_caption =\n| location    = Bridgewater Plaza<br />[[Moneta, Virginia]]\n| target      = Alison Parker and Adam Ward\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37.14330|-79.67027|type:event_region:US-VA|display=inline,title}}\n| date        = {{start date|2015|08|26}}\n| time        = '''Shooting''': 6:46 a.m.<br />'''Manhunt''' 6:46 a.m.&nbsp;\u2013 {{circa}} 11:30 a.m.\n| timezone    = EDT\n| type        = Murder\u2013suicide\n| fatalities  = 3 (including the perpetrator)\n| injuries    = 1\n| victims     = <!-- or | victim      = -->\n| perpetrator = Vester Lee Flanagan II (aka Bryce Williams)<!-- or | perpetrator = -->  <!-- alias: | perps = or | perp = -->\n| susperps    = <!-- or | susperp     = -->\n| weapons     =  [[Glock|Glock 19]] 9mm pistol<ref name=SunTimes.Obtained>{{cite web|last1=Merda|first1=Chad|title=ATF: Virginia gunman passed background check, obtained gun legally|url=http://national.suntimes.com/national-world-news/7/72/1720021/atf-vester-flanagan-passed-background-check-obtained-gun-legally|website=Chicago Sun-Times|publisher=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=September 1, 2015|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Telegraph.Unanswered>{{cite news|last1=Hodari|first1=David|title=Virginia news shooting: the unanswered questions|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/11829434/Virginia-news-shooting-the-unanswered-questions.html|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=September 1, 2015|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Vester Flanagan Bought Gun Legally From Virginia Dealer, Officials Say|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/virginia-tv-shooting/vester-flanagan-bought-gun-legally-virginia-dealer-officials-say-n417136|author=Pete Williams|author2=Andrew Blankstein|author3=Tom Winter|website=NBC News|publisher=NBC News Group, LLC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 28, 2015|author-link=Pete Williams (journalist)}}</ref>\n| numparts    = <!-- or | numpart     = -->\n| dfens       = <!-- or | dfen        = -->\n| motive      = Perceived workplace animosity, supposed revenge for the [[Charleston church shooting]]<ref name=cnn.virginia.shooting>{{cite news|title=Police: Bryce Williams fatally shoots self after killing journalists on air|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/26/us/virginia-shooting-wdbj/|author=Eliott C. McLaughlin|author2=Catherine E. Shoichet|website=CNN|publisher=Time Warner|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n| website     = <!-- URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\nNews reporter Alison Parker and photojournalist Adam Ward were employees of CBS affiliate [[WDBJ]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia]] who were fatally shot on August 26, 2015, while conducting a live television interview near [[Smith Mountain Lake]] in [[Moneta, Virginia|Moneta]]. They were interviewing Vicki Gardner, executive director of the local chamber of commerce, when all three were attacked by a gunman. Parker, age 24, and Ward, age 27, died at the scene, while Gardner survived.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two WDBJ7 employees killed in attack at Bridgewater Plaza|url=http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/law-enforcement-investigating-incident-at-bridgewater-plaza/34923086|author=Web Staff|website=[[WDBJ]]|publisher=Schurz Communications|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826131524/http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/law-enforcement-investigating-incident-at-bridgewater-plaza/34923086|archivedate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> The gunman was 41-year-old Vester Lee Flanagan II, also known by the professional pseudonym of Bryce Williams, a former reporter at WDBJ. The station fired him for disruptive conduct in 2013.<ref name=\"nytimes_20150826\">{{cite news|title=Virginia TV Reporter and Photographer Shot During Live Broadcast|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/us/wdbj7-virginia-journalists-shot-during-live-broadcast.html|first=Katie|last=Rogers|author2=Alan Blinder| newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> After a five-hour manhunt, Flanagan shot himself during a car chase with police officers and died later at a hospital.<ref name=\"usat_Susp\">{{cite web|title=Suspect in on-air murder of journalists kills himself|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/08/26/reports-two-dead-virginia-shooting-live-tv/32391633/|first=John|last=Bacon|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=USAToday.Angered/><ref name=ShotHimself>{{Cite web|title = WDBJ Shooting Suspect Shot Himself, Died in Hospital|url = http://www.whsv.com/home/headlines/Roanoke-News-Crew-Involved-in-Shooting-Incident-322939771.html|website = WHSV 3|accessdate = October 25, 2015|last = Williamson|first = Jeff|date = August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n\n===Murders===\nParker and Ward were conducting a live interview with Gardner at Bridgewater Plaza in Moneta about upcoming events for the 50th anniversary of [[Smith Mountain Lake]], {{convert|26|mi}} southeast of Roanoke. The shooting occurred at 6:46&nbsp;a.m. Eastern Time in the middle of the segment, which was broadcast on WDBJ's morning news program ''Mornin{{'}}''. Video of the incident showed Parker conducting the interview when at least eight gunshots were heard, followed by screams. Ward's camera fell to the ground, briefly capturing the image of Flanagan holding a [[Glock|Glock 19]] 9mm pistol.<ref name=SunTimes.Obtained/><ref name=Telegraph.Unanswered/>\n\nWDBJ production master control operators then switched back to ''Mornin{{'}}'' anchor Kimberly McBroom at the station's news studio, seemingly confused by what had just happened. She later said that she believed the noises could have been a car backfiring or shots being fired in the background.<ref>{{cite news|title=News anchor thought car backfired when gunman shot colleagues on air|url=http://www.9news.com.au/world/2015/08/27/15/03/news-anchor-thought-car-backfired-after-colleagues-murdered-on-air|website=Nine News|publisher=Nine Entertainment Co.|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Immediate aftermath===\nParker and Ward died at the scene. Gardner was also shot, but she survived following surgery at [[Carilion Roanoke Memorial Hospital]].<ref>\n*{{Cite web|title = Family of Vicki Gardner issues statement: 'We are grateful'|url = http://wtvr.com/2015/08/28/family-of-vicki-gardner-issues-statement-we-are-grateful/|website = WTVR.com|accessdate = August 30, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Reporter and cameraman killed during live broadcast|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/reporter-and-cameraman-killed-during-live-broadcast|first=Anna|last=Brand|website=MSNBC|publisher=NBC News|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Fired reporter kills 2 former co-workers on live TV|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/379b43ac8db44392a594ee48ed889a84/manager-2-virginia-tv-station-workers-fatally-shot-air|first=Steve|last=Helber|author2=Pam Ramsey|author3=Jonathan Drew|agency=Associated Press|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Vicki Gardner declared 'poster child' for bullet wound recovery at CRMH|url=http://wsls.com/2015/08/31/vicki-gardner-declared-poster-child-for-bullet-wound-recovery-at-crmh/|work=WSLS10|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> According to the state medical examiner's office, Parker died from gunshot wounds to her head and chest, while Ward died from shots to his head and torso.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia shootings: Slain TV journalists shot both in head and body|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/virginia-shootings-slain-tv-journalists-shot-both-in-head-and-body-1.3207446|website=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref> Gardner was shot in the back after she curled into a fetal position in an attempt to play dead.<ref name=\"nyt_gardner\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2015/10/07/tv-shooting-survivor-vicki-gardner-intv-ac-cutdown.cnn|title=WDBJ shooting survivor: 'I played dead'|work=CNN|date=October 7, 2015|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> A total of 15 shots were fired.<ref name=Heavy.Facts>{{cite web|title=Vester Lee Flanagan: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|url=http://heavy.com/news/2015/08/lester-lee-flanagan-flanighan-flanigan-wdbj-tv-disgruntled-employee-virginia-shooting-suspect-cameraman-photos-video-chase-gun-gunman-arrested/|first=Tom|last=Cleary|website=heavy.com|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nStaff in the WDBJ newsroom  reviewed video of the incident from Ward's fallen camera and identified Flanagan as the likely gunman. They alerted general manager Jeffrey Marks, who passed the information to the county sheriff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia TV Shooting: Chilling Image Alerted Station to Killer Vester Flanagan|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/virginia-tv-shooting/virginia-tv-shooting-chilling-image-alerted-station-killer-vester-flanagan-n416826|first=Erin|last=McClam|website=NBC News|publisher=NBC News Group, LLC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan faxed ABC News at 8:23&nbsp;a.m. and then phoned shortly after 10:00&nbsp;a.m., making a confession.<ref name=Jack/> During the ensuing manhunt, authorities tracked Flanagan's cell phone to locate him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia gunman details grievances in lengthy 'suicide note,' references Charleston church shooting|url=http://fox8.com/2015/08/26/virginia-gunman-details-grievances-in-lengthy-suicide-note-references-charleston-church-shooting/|agency=[[CNN]]wire|website=WJW|publisher=Tribune Broadcasting|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlanagan abandoned his [[Ford Mustang]] at the [[Roanoke\u2013Blacksburg Regional Airport]] and drove a rented [[Chevrolet Sonic]] north on [[I-81]], then east on [[I-66]]. An automated license plate reader in a Virginia state trooper's car identified the rented Sonic at 11:20&nbsp;a.m. The trooper called for backup and attempted to initiate a traffic stop, but Flanagan sped away. His car ran off the side of the road and struck an embankment near [[Markham, Fauquier County, Virginia|Markham]] after a pursuit of less than two miles.<ref name=markham>{{cite news|title=TV murder suspect fatally shoots himself in Fauquier|url=http://www.fauquiernow.com/index.php/fauquier_news/article/fauquier-tv-murder-suspect-kills-himself-in-fauquier-2015|work=Fauquier Now|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> He was found inside the car with gunshot wounds<ref name=\"USAToday.Angered\" /> which were apparently self-inflicted while he was driving.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suspect in Virginia Shooting of News Team Commits Suicide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/us/wdbj7-virginia-journalists-shot-during-live-broadcast.html?_r=0|first=Hawes|last=Spencer|author2=Katie Rogers|author3=Alan Blinder|author4=Richard P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He was airlifted to [[Inova Fairfax Hospital]] in [[Falls Church, Virginia|Falls Church]], where he was declared dead at 1:26&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=ShotHimself/><ref>{{cite news|title=Suspect in On-Air Shooting Dies From Self-Inflicted Wound|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/suspect-air-shooting-dead-inflicted-wound/story?id=33327920|first=Meghan|last=Keneally|website=ABC News|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=WPost.Slaying>{{cite news|title=Suspect in slaying of two TV station employees in SW Virginia shoots himself and dies|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2015/08/26/tv-camera-crew-caught-in-active-shooter-situation-in-southwest-virginia/|first=Dana|last=Hedgpeth|author2=Justin Jouvenal|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\n[[File:Alison Parker and Adam Ward.jpg|thumb|Parker and Ward, from WDBJ7's [[Twitter]] account]]\n'''Alison Bailey Parker'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heralddemocrat.com/article/20150828/NEWS/308289872|title=Austin College alumni and staff mourn slain newscaster|publisher=}}</ref> (August 19, 1991 \u2013 August 26, 2015) grew up in [[Martinsville, Virginia]] and attended [[Patrick Henry Community College]] and [[James Madison University]]. She interned at WDBJ in 2012, worked as a general assignment news reporter at ABC affiliate [[WCTI-TV]] in [[New Bern, North Carolina]] from December 2012 until May 2014,<ref>{{cite web|title=Former WCTI reporter killed during TV live shot|url=http://www.wcti12.com/news/former-wcti-reporter-killed-during-tv-live-shot/34924588|first=Jaime|last=McCutcheon|website=[[WCTI-TV]]|publisher=[[Bonten Media Group]]|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826180157/http://www.wcti12.com/news/former-wcti-reporter-killed-during-tv-live-shot/34924588|archivedate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> and then was hired by WDBJ in 2014 as a correspondent for ''Mornin{{'}}''.<ref name=cnn.virginia.shooting/><ref>{{cite web|title=A look at the lives of WDBJ7's Alison Parker and Adam Ward|url=http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/a-look-at-the-lives-of-wdbj7s-alison-parker-and-adam-ward/34929588|first=Joe|last=Dashiell|website=WDBJ|publisher=Schurz Communications|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828050405/http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/a-look-at-the-lives-of-wdbj7s-alison-parker-and-adam-ward/34929588|archivedate=August 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Adam Laing Ward'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2015/08/26/adam-ward-wdbj7-photojournalist/32411325/|title=WDBJ7 TV: Adam Ward was a 'fine photojournalist'|website=USA TODAY}}</ref> (May 10, 1988 \u2013 August 26, 2015) grew up in [[Salem, Virginia]] and graduated from [[Virginia Tech]] with a degree in communications and media studies in 2011. He had worked at the station since July 2011 as a videographer, as well as an occasional sports reporter.<ref>{{cite web|title=WDBJ reporter Alison Parker, photographer Adam Ward hailed by colleagues, friends|url=http://wtvr.com/2015/08/26/wdbj-reporter-alison-parker-photographer-adam-ward-hailed-by-colleagues-friends/|website=WTVR-TV|publisher=Tribune Broadcasting|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Andy Parker criticizes Senators\">{{cite news|title=WDBJ reporter's father criticizes senators for not calling family|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/28/politics/alison-parker-shooting-wdbj-father-andy-parker-senators/|first=Eugene|last=Scott|author2=Ted Barrett|website=CNN|publisher=Time Warner|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVicki Gardner is originally from [[Union Springs, New York]] and has been the executive director of the Smith Mountain Lake Regional Chamber of Commerce since 2002.<ref name=WPost.Head>{{cite web|title=Shooting victim Vicki Gardner is head of local chamber of commerce|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/third-victim-in-virginia-shooting-is-head-of-local-chamber-of-commerce/2015/08/26/1ad878a4-4c03-11e5-bfb9-9736d04fc8e4_story.html|first=Antonio|last=Olivo|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> She underwent surgery in which her kidney and part of her colon were removed<ref name=\"nyt_gardner\" /> and was released from the hospital on September 8, 2015.<ref name=\"nyt_gardner\">{{cite web|first=Christine|last=Hauser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/09/us/woman-injured-in-virginia-tv-shooting-is-out-of-the-hospital.html|title=Woman Injured in Virginia TV Shooting Is Out of the Hospital|work=The New York Times|date=September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Vester Lee Flanagan\n|image       = <!--do not add image per FFD-->\n|birth_name  = Vester Lee Flanagan II\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1973|10|8}}<ref name=\"CBI\">{{cite web|author=California Birth Index |title=Vester L Flanagan, Born 10/08/1973 in California|url=http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/vester_l_flanagan_born_1973_11921659|publisher=California Birth Index|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Oakland, California]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|2015|8|26|1973|10|8}} \n|death_place = [[Falls Church, Virginia]], U.S.\n|death_cause = Self-inflicted gunshot wounds\n|residence   = [[Roanoke, Virginia]], U.S.\n|nationality = American\n|occupation  = Television news journalist; former model\n|education   = [[San Francisco State University]]\n|other_names = Bryce Williams\n}}\n\n===Personal background===\nVester Lee Flanagan II (October 8, 1973 \u2013 August 26, 2015) was known professionally as Bryce Williams and was a native of [[Oakland, California]]. His family were [[Jehovah's Witnesses]].<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web |last1=Matt Pearce, Lee Romney and Natalie Schachar |title=Suspect in killing of Virginia TV crew said he was 'just waiting to go BOOM' |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-virginia-tv-station-workers-fatally-shot-on-air-20150826-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=August 26, 2019 |ref=latimes |date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He graduated from [[Skyline High School (Oakland, California)|Skyline High School]] and attended [[San Francisco State University]], earning a degree in radio and television in 1995. He interned at CBS affiliate [[KPIX-TV|KPIX]] in [[San Francisco]] in 1993, eventually working there as a production assistant and weekend news writer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suspected killer in Virginia slayings had Bay Area ties|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Suspected-killer-in-Virginia-slayings-of-6466587.php|first=Evan|last=Sernoffsky|author2=Kurtis Alexander|author3=Jenna Lyons|author4=Rachel Swan|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|publisher=Hearst Corporation|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He had been a small-time actor and model before beginning his career in journalism.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia shooter Vester Lee Flanagan is former model, 'high paid companion'; had sued news station for discrimination|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/gunman-posts-video-showing-fatal-shooting-tv-reporter-article-1.2337769|first=Melissa|last=Chan|newspaper=New York Daily News|publisher=Daily News, L.P.|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlanagan worked as a general assignment news reporter at CBS affiliate [[WTOC-TV]] in [[Savannah, Georgia]] from February 1997 to March 1999.<ref name=CBS.Blamed>{{cite web|title=Report: Suspect in deadly on-air attack blamed Charleston shooting|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/wdbj-shootig-suspect-vester-lee-flanagan-suspect-in-deadly-virginia-television-shooting-of-alison|website=CBS News|publisher=CBS Interactive|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He worked as a reporter for NBC affiliate [[WTWC-TV]] in [[Tallahassee, Florida]] between March 1999 and March 2000. He later reported to news director Don Shafer that co-workers were making offensive comments about his sexual orientation. In an interview with the ''Daily Mail'', former WTWC sports reporter Dave Leval said that Flanagan verbally abused two female staffers at the station on different occasions after they pointed out mistakes in his reporting, and several photographers tried to get out of working on stories to which Flanagan was assigned due to his \"diva\" behavior.<ref>\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiego6.com/news/local/SD6-News-Director-hired-and-fired-suspect-in-2000-in-FL-322971901.html#|title=SD6 News Director hired, fired WDBJ shooting suspect at FL station in 2000|last=Hood|first=Lindsay|date=August 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109210323/http://www.sandiego6.com/news/local/SD6-News-Director-hired-and-fired-suspect-in-2000-in-FL-322971901.html|archive-date=November 9, 2015|url-status=dead|publisher=Bay City Television/Grupo Televisa|agency=City News Service|first2=Laura|last2=Nguyen|website=XETV-TDT|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}\n*{{cite news|title=Former News Director: Roanoke Killer Would Get Into Physical Conflicts With Staff|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/ex-colleagues-of-virginia-gunman-say-many-tried-to-mentor-and-support-him/2015/08/28/07d2598e-4da5-11e5-84df-923b3ef1a64b_story.html|first=Kerry|last=Picket|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlanagan lost his job due to \"odd behavior\" in March 2000, and he filed a civil lawsuit against WTWC alleging racial discrimination, as he was African-American. The lawsuit was settled under unspecified terms in January 2001. WTWC's owner [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] had discontinued the station's news operations in November 2000 due to poor ratings and budget reductions.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Flanagan worked for CBS affiliate [[WNCT-TV]] in [[Greenville, North Carolina]] from 2002 to 2004.<ref name=CBS.Blamed/><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Here's What We Know About The Virginia Shooting Suspect|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/davidmack/heres-what-we-know-about-the-virginia-tv-shooter|first=David|last=Mack|website=BuzzFeed|publisher=BuzzFeed Inc.|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also found some work at ABC affiliate [[KMID]] in [[Midland, Texas]].<ref name=Heavy.Facts/>\n\n===Tenure at WDBJ===\nWDBJ announced on April 19, 2012 that they hired Flanagan as a multimedia journalist under the professional name Bryce Williams.<ref name=adweek1>{{cite web|title=WDBJ Adds Two Veteran Reporters|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/wdbj-adds-two-veteran-reporters/46832|first=Andrew|last=Gauthier|website=[[AdWeek|TVSpy]]|publisher=Mediabistro Holdings|date=April 19, 2012|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Documents relating to his time at WDBJ suggest that the station's management considered him an experienced reporter, but there were conflicts with other reporters and with photographers.<ref name=NYTimes.Turbulent>{{cite news|title=Documents Show Vester Lee Flanagan's Turbulent Tenure at TV Station Before Virginia Shooting|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/us/documents-show-virginia-shooting-suspects-turbulent-tenure-at-tv-station.html|first=Alan|last=Blinder|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Office memos from WDBJ showed that news director Dan Dennison ordered him to contact [[Health Advocate]] in July 2012 after receiving complaints that co-workers were \"feeling threatened or uncomfortable\" while working with him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia shootings: Gunman ordered to seek medical help|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-34070393|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> It is unclear whether he did so prior to his dismissal.<ref name=FOX.Inside>{{cite news|title=Inside Vester Lee Flanagan's life|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2015/08/27/inside-vester-lee-flanagan-life|website=Fox News|publisher=Fox News Network, LLC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWDBJ dismissed Flanagan on February 1, 2013 because of his volatile behavior. According to a former colleague, upon learning of his dismissal, Flanagan lashed out at news room staffers, resulting in the staffers being put in a room while police escorted him out of the building. Ward allegedly recorded Flanagan as he was escorted out, and the two men had a confrontation earlier that day. Flanagan allegedly threw a wooden cross at Dennison, saying, \"You need this.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Vester Flanagan told to seek medical help by Virginia TV station, say memos|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/aug/26/virginia-gunman-vester-flanagan-wdbj-2012-memos-medical-help|first=Lauren|last=Gambino|author2=Jon Swaine|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> WDBJ provided security to the staffers for a time after the incident and directed them to call the police if he ever returned to the station.<ref name=NYTimes.Turbulent/><ref>\n*{{cite news|title=Bryce Williams: A meticulous plan for a live televised murder|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/27/us/virginia-shooting-wdbj-bryce-williams-parker-adams/index.html|author1=Ben Brumfield|author2=Eliott C. McLaughlin|author3=Catherine E. Shoichet|website=CNN|publisher=Time Warner|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite web|title=Accused WDBJ Killer Shoots Self; Had Been Fired From Station in 2013|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/wdbj-shooter-was-a-known-problem/154167|first=Kevin|last=Eck|website=TVSpy|publisher=Mediabistro Holdings|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan filed an [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission|EEOC]] complaint against WDBJ, alleging racial discrimination, and he allegedly named Parker in it. The EEOC investigated, then dismissed the complaint as uncorroborated.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>\n*{{cite web|title=Virginia TV shooter posts chilling video|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2015/08/virginia_tv_shooter_posts_chil.html|first=Leada|last=Gore|newspaper=[[The Birmingham News]]|publisher=Advance Publications|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Vester Flanagan: Everything we know about the gunman who killed two WDBJ journalists on-air|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/police-hunt-former-news-anchor-vester-flanagan-in-the-killing-of-two-wbdj-journalists-10473200.html|first=Justin|last=Carissimo|newspaper=The Independent|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan wrote a suicide note in which he said that he killed both of his cats out of rage after the incident.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/28/us/vester-lee-flanagan-grievances-homicidal-explosion.html?referrer=&_r=1|date=August 27, 2015|work=The New York Times|title=A Life of Listing Grievances, and Then Virginia Gunman's Final Homicidal Explosion|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/vester-flanagan-virginia-news-crew-shooter-killed-two-cats-murders-366599|title=Vester Flanagan, Virginia News Crew Shooter, Killed Two Cats Before Murders|work=Newsweek|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}\n*{{Cite journal|title = Inside the Warped Mind of Vester Flanagan and Other Shooters|url = https://newrepublic.com/article/122669/injustice-collectors-how-understand-vester-flanagans-manifesto|journal = The New Republic|date = September 23, 2015|accessdate = October 5, 2015|author = Dave Cullen}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his dismissal, Flanagan got a job at a local [[UnitedHealth Group]] call center. He had a confrontation with a female employee who casually pointed out how quiet he was being, to which he responded aggressively, telling her to never talk to him again.<ref>{{cite news|title=On-air shooter threatened to make 'headlines,' showed anger|url=https://news.yahoo.com/air-killings-gripped-millions-social-media-storm-071552249.html|first=Adam|last=Geller|author2=Alan Suderman|website=Yahoo! News|publisher=Yahoo!|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> One of Flanagan's neighbors in his apartment complex described him as an arrogant person who acted rudely towards people around him. He was noted for sometimes throwing cat feces at the homes of neighbors with whom he had disputes.<ref name=FOX.Inside/>\n\n===Shooting and motives===\n{{tweet|name= Bryce Williams|username=bryce_williams7 |number=636556064285151232 |date=August 26, 2015 |text=Alison made racist comments|unverified =y|reference =<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schultz |first1=Marisa |last2=Rosario |first2=Frank |title=The comments that became a reporter's death sentence |url=https://nypost.com/2015/08/28/reporters-everyday-comments-deemed-racist-by-on-air-killer/ |accessdate=September 26, 2018 |work=[[New York Post]] |date=August 28, 2015}}</ref> }}\nFlanagan maintained accounts on [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] which were suspended after he was named as a suspect in the shooting. He repeated his claims of racial discrimination by WDBJ on both profiles, specifically naming Parker and Ward. He claimed that Parker had made a coded racist remark during her internship at WDBJ regarding a friend of Flanagan's, and that Ward had filed a complaint against him to WDBJ's human resources department after working with him on one occasion.<ref name=\"usatoday_anger\">{{cite news|title=Former co-workers say Vester Flanagan had problems with work, anger, racism|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/08/28/former-co-workers-say-vester-flanagan-had-problems-work-anger-racism/71339660/|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 29, 2015|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt 11:14&nbsp;a.m. on the day of the shooting, Flanagan uploaded a 56-second phone camera video to his Twitter and Facebook accounts before they were suspended, shot from a first-person perspective of the incident.<ref>\n*{{cite news|title=Chilling video shows gunman's perspective of on-air shooting in Virginia|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/08/26/two-dead-virginia-shooting-live-tv-social-media/32401101/|first=Emily|last=Brown|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=The Latest: Police had contact with killer after firing|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/the-latest-on-tv-shooting-husband-overjoyed-wife-is-alive/2015/08/27/064da9b0-4d23-11e5-80c2-106ea7fb80d4_story.html|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> The video shows him walking up to the scene of the interview and brandishing a handgun for approximately 15 seconds without Ward, Parker, or Gardner noticing; Gardner later said that she had been blinded by the television lighting.<ref name=\"gardner\">{{cite news|title=Virginia shooting: injured woman says she did not see gunman before he fired|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/aug/29/virginia-tv-news-shooting-vicki-gardner-injured-woman|newspaper=The Guardian|date=August 29, 2015|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref> He mutters \"bitch\" while pointing the weapon at Parker, and lowers the gun before raising it again and opening fire directly at her. Parker flinches and screams before attempting to escape the attack, and the light of Ward's camera is seen quickly dropping before Flanagan pulls the camera away and shuts it off.<ref name=NYDailyNews.Broadcast/><ref>\n*{{cite web|title=Alleged Newscast Gunman Shoots Self After Posting Vid Of Shooting|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/vester-flanagan-tweets-shooting|first=Caitlin|last=McNeal|website=[[Talking Points Memo]]|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Reporter, photographer shot to death on air in Virginia; suspect dies at hospital|url=http://my.chicagotribune.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-84289393/|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Ex-coworker shoots, kills news crew on live TV in Virginia|url=http://abc7chicago.com/news/ex-coworker-kills-virginia-news-crew-on-live-tv-/958110/|author=Chuck Goudie|author2=Ross Weidner|author3=Ann Pistone|author4=Christine Tressel|author5=Barbara Markoff|website=WLS-TV|publisher=ABC Owned Television Stations|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nABC News received a 23-page fax at 8:26&nbsp;a.m. allegedly sent by Flanagan<ref>{{cite news|title=Suspect in On-Air Virginia Shooting Identified|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/tv-reporter-camerman-killed-gunman-opens-fire-virginia/story?id=33327920|author=Meghan Keneally via Good Morning America|website=ABC News|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> entitled \"Suicide Note for Friend & Family\". He described his grievances over what he alleged to be racial discrimination and sexual harassment committed by black men and white women in his workplace, believing that he was targeted because he was a homosexual black man.<ref name=USAToday.Angered>{{cite news|title=Disturbed' Va. gunman angered by Charleston shootings|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/08/26/alleged-va-shooter-had-history-workplace-racism-complaints/32404967/|first=Doug|last=Stanglin|author2=Tyler Pager|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Jack>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/beta/US/shooting-alleged-gunman-details-grievances-suicide-notes/story?id=33336339|title=After Shooting, Alleged Gunman Details Grievances in 'Suicide Notes'|first=Pierre|last=Thomas|author2=Jack Cloherty|author3=Jack Date|author4=Mike Levine|website=ABC News|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=reuters_powder_keg>{{cite news|title=Virginia TV journalists killed by suspect with 'powder keg' of anger|url=https://news.yahoo.com/two-virginia-television-journalists-fatally-shot-air-attack-130244085.html|first=Gary|last=Robertson|agency=[[Reuters]]|website=Yahoo! News|publisher=Yahoo!|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan claimed to have been provoked by the [[Charleston church shooting]] two months before and made threatening comments about [[Dylann Roof]], the perpetrator of that crime.<ref name=NYDailyNews.Broadcast>{{cite news |title=TV news reporter, cameraman are fatally shot during live broadcast in Virginia; suspected shooter posts video of attack, then kills himself |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/shot-live-tv-news-broadcast-virginia-article-1.2337586 |first=Jason |last=Silverstein |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=August 26, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He described the church shooting as a \"tipping point\", saying that his anger had been \"building steadily\" and describing himself as \"a human powder keg\u2026 just waiting to go BOOM\".<ref name=USAToday.Angered /> A spokesman for the Franklin County Sheriff's Office said that Flanagan \"very closely identified\" with \"individuals who have committed domestic acts of violence and mass murder, as well as the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001 attacks]] on the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Vester Flanagan 'very closely identified' with foreign, domestic terrorists: Police|url=http://www.cbs12.com/news/top-stories/stories/vester-flanagan-very-closely-identified-foreign-domestic-terrorists-police-28780.shtml|work=CBS12.com|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> He said that [[Jehovah]] had told him to act and expressed an admiration for [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]], who perpetrated the 1999 [[Columbine High School massacre]]; and [[Seung-Hui Cho]], the perpetrator of the 2007 [[Virginia Tech shooting]].<ref name=Jack/><ref>{{cite news|title=Vester Lee Flanagan II, aka Bryce Williams, Named as Suspect in Live TV Shooting in Virginia|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/vester-lee-flanagan-ii-named-suspect-live-tv-shootings-virginia-n416331|first=Erin|last=McClam|website=NBC News|publisher=NBC News|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Flanagan said in the note, \"Yeah I'm all fucked up in the head.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=What we know so far about Vester Lee Flanagan, the man who shot dead two journalists on TV|url=http://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/life/current-affairs/what-we-know-so-far-about-vester-lee-flanagan-man-who-shot-dead-two-journalists-tv/|website=bailiwickexpress.com|accessdate=September 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter Flanagan's death, officers searched his rental car and found various items, including a [[Glock]] pistol with several [[Magazine (firearms)|magazines]] and ammunition, a cell phone, letters, notes, a \"to-do\" list, a suitcase containing three license plates, and several disguises, including a wig.<ref name=FOX.Inside/><ref name=WPost.Prepared>{{cite news|title=In Roanoke shooter's car, signs he was prepared to remain on the run|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/journalists-cope-a-day-after-fatal-shooting-of-colleagues-in-roanoke/2015/08/27/34c5f40e-4cbb-11e5-bfb9-9736d04fc8e4_story.html|first=Justin|last=Jouvenal|author2=Julie Zauzmer|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===Reactions===\nPresident [[Barack Obama]] said that he was heartbroken over the murders,<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama On Virginia Shooting: 'It Breaks My Heart'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/obama-virginia-shooting_55de347fe4b0e7117ba8c664|first=Paige|last=Lavender|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=AOL|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> and Virginia Governor [[Terry McAuliffe]] said on Twitter that he also was heartbroken over the shooting, and he reasserted his support for gun control.<ref name=WPost.Slaying/> He later made calls for tougher gun laws in the state and blamed the state legislature for failing to pass a package of gun control measures that he had proposed earlier in January.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gov. Terry McAuliffe Calls For Tougher Gun Laws After Virginia Shooting|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/terry-mcauliffe-gun-control-virginia-shooting_55ddd4fbe4b0a40aa3acea2f|first=Kim|last=Bellware|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=AOL|date=August 26, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> His remarks drew criticism from Republicans, who said that he was politicizing the tragedy.<ref name=WPost.Prepared/> Virginia Senator [[Mark Warner]] gave his condolences to Parker and Ward's families, as well as to WDBJ and the first responders involved.<ref name=WPost.Slaying/>\n\nParker's father Andy Parker said that he would become an advocate on the issue of gun violence prevention, comparing it to [[John Walsh (television host)|John Walsh]]'s advocacy of crime prevention, and he said that he would speak with politicians and news outlets to address issues of mental health and improving care for those with mental illnesses. He had run as a Democratic candidate for the Virginia House of Delegates in 2007 but was not elected, and he urged politicians to strengthen laws against gun violence. His comments were made against pressure from the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA), whom he criticized for preventing Senators and Representatives from passing such legislation in the past. He criticized Virginia Senators [[Tim Kaine]], who criticized the NRA for blocking efforts by the Virginia General Assembly and Congress to tighten background checks for gun purchases, and Mark Warner for not directly contacting his family following the announcement that his daughter was one of the victims.<ref name=\"Andy Parker criticizes Senators\"/><ref name=\"HuffPo-CTV\">\n*{{cite news|title=Slain Reporter's Father Fears For His Safety As He Takes Up Gun Control Activism|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/andy-parker-gun-control-alison-parker_55e0af1be4b0b7a96338e827|first=Amanda|last=Terkel|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=AOL|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Slain journalist's father says he'll push for stricter gun laws in U.S.|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/slain-journalist-s-father-says-he-ll-push-for-stricter-gun-laws-in-u-s-1.2536192|first=Emily|last=Chan|website=[[CTV News]]|publisher=[[Bell Media]]|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nStaff members for Senator Kaine explained that Kaine had not contacted the victims' families at the time \"out of respect for their space and privacy during this difficult time of grieving\". The same reasoning was cited by Mark Warner on August 29, who said he did not immediately contact Parker's family out of respect to the family's privacy \"at a time of unimaginable grief\".<ref name=\"Andy Parker criticizes Senators\"/><ref name=\"HuffPo-CTV\"/>\n\nThe shooting led Alison Parker's boyfriend [[Chris Hurst (Virginia politician)|Chris Hurst]] to successfully run for a seat in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] with a priority to pass gun safety legislation.<ref name=\"Graun\">[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/feb/22/wdbj-shooting-chris-hurst-virginia-alison-parker-joseph-yost Boyfriend of reporter killed on live TV aims to unseat NRA-endorsed lawmaker], by Lois Beckett, at ''[[the Guardian]]''; published February 22, 2017. Retrieved November 8, 2017</ref>\n\n===Media response===\nIn the immediate wake of the shooting, various media productions were either delayed or pulled from television outlets. The first-season finale of the series ''[[Mr. Robot (TV series)|Mr. Robot]]'' was postponed one week from its originally scheduled air date (the day of the murders) because the episode included a scene with similarities to the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/08/26/usa-mr-robot-finale-postponed-virginia-live-tv-shooting/32430401/|title='Mr. Robot' finale delayed after Va. murders|first=Bill|last=Keveney|date=August 27, 2015|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> [[IFC (U.S. TV network)|IFC]] delayed airing an episode of its satirical series ''[[Documentary Now!]]'' which centered on two journalists who are killed on-camera as they track down a Mexican drug cartel leader.<ref>\n*{{cite web|title=IFC Delays 'Documentary Now' Episode After News Team's On-Air Shooting|url=http://deadline.com/2015/08/documentary-delayed-by-ifc-now-following-virginia-shooting-1201508476/|first=Erik|last=Pedersen|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}\n*{{cite web|title=IFC's 'Documentary Now!' Delays Episode Due to Virginia Shooting|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/documentary-now-wdbj-shooting-virginia-1201580024/|first=Whitney|last=Friedlander|website=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> [[Warner Records|Warner Bros. Records]] decided to pull a television commercial for [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]'s album ''[[Immortalized (Disturbed album)|Immortalized]]'', as it depicted an incident similar to the killings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disturbed Album Ad Pulled After Eerie Parallels to On-Air Shooting|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/disturbed-album-ad-pulled-after-eerie-parallels-to-127737096001.html|author=Billy Johnson Jr.|website=Yahoo! Music|publisher=Yahoo!|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWriting about news coverage of the incident, [[ThinkProgress]] noted, \"There isn\u2019t broad consensus about how to handle this type of coverage.\"<ref name=thinkprogress/> Users of [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] criticized the sites' autoplay option, which allowed opted-in viewers to see graphic images of the shooting without warning.<ref>\n*{{cite news|title=Facebook and Twitter users complain over Virginia shooting videos autoplay|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/aug/27/facebook-twitter-users-complain-virginia-shooting-videos-autoplay|first=Samuel|last=Gibbs|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite news|title=Virginia murders show ugly side of autoplay|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/08/26/technology/autoplay-twitter-facebook-virginia-shooter/|author=Sara Ashley O'Brien|website=CNN Money|publisher=Time Warner|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> The ''New York Post'', the ''New York Daily News'', and British tabloids ''The Daily Mirror'' and ''The Sun'' were criticized for their decision to publish still frames from Flanagan's phone video of the murders on their front pages.<ref>\n*{{cite news|title='New York Daily News' cover causes outrage over graphic images of slain journalist|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2015/08/27/new-york-daily-news-virginia-reporters-murdered-live-tv-newspaper-cover/32469823/|first=Mary|last=Bowerman|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}\n*{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Withnall |date=August 27, 2015 |title=Virginia shooting: New York Daily News and other newspapers spark outrage with front pages 'letting killer tell the story' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/virginia-shooting-new-york-daily-news-and-other-newspapers-spark-outrage-with-front-pages-letting-killer-tell-the-story-10474159.html |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> ''ABC World News Tonight'' did not show any part of Flanagan's video, ''NBC Nightly News'' broadcast a still frame, and ''CBS Evening News'' showed a 25-second segment of the video.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Ariens |date=August 27, 2015 |title=Of Evening Broadcasts, Only CBS Showed Gunman's Video of Deadly Shooting |url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/only-cbs-news-showed-gunmans-video-of-deadly-shooting/270539 |website=TVNewser |publisher=Mediabistro Holdings |accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> CNN aired the footage once every hour on the day of the shooting.<ref name=thinkprogress>{{cite web |first=Tara |last=Culp-Ressler |date=August 26, 2015 |title=The Media's Ethical Dilemma About How To Handle Footage Of People Shot On Live TV |url=https://thinkprogress.org/the-medias-ethical-dilemma-about-how-to-handle-footage-of-people-shot-on-live-tv-db2c3943c04d |website=ThinkProgress |accessdate=December 15, 2016 }}</ref> The gun control lobbying group [[Everytown for Gun Safety]] shared the broadcast video with a three-second discretionary warning, despite WDBJ's plea on Twitter not to \"share or post the video\".<ref name=Kaufman>{{cite news |first=Alexander C. |last=Kaufman |date=August 26, 2015 |title=A Major Gun Control Group Wants You to Watch the Virginia Shooting Video |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/gun-control-virginia-shooting_us_55de1c09e4b0a40aa3ad46d2 |website=The Huffington Post |accessdate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nChristine Courtois chairs the [[American Psychological Association]]'s post-traumatic stress disorder guidelines development panel, and she warned that anyone watching the footage was likely to be upset, possibly leading to acute stress disorder.<ref>{{cite news|title=The murders that rocked breakfast television|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-34047643|first=Vanessa|last=Barford|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> ''The Guardian'' journalist [[Catherine Bennett (journalist)|Catherine Bennett]] criticized the media's use of frame shots and footage as \"helping Flanagan achieve his vanity script.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Catherine |last=Bennett |date=August 29, 2015 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/30/alison-parker-adam-ward-vester-flanagan-tv-shooting |title=Nobody had to see Alison Parker's terror as she faced death |website=The Guardian |accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref> ''Ebony'' writer [[Jamilah Lemieux]]<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Jamilah |last=Lemieux |date=August 27, 2015 |title=[WDBJ TRAGEDY] Death Videos, Grief and Complicated Emotions |url=http://www.ebony.com/news-views/wdbj-tragedy-death-videos-grief-and-complicated-emotions-543 |magazine=Ebony |accessdate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref> and Dexter Thomas of the ''Los Angeles Times''<ref>{{cite web |first=Dexter |last=Thomas |title=Are we afraid to watch white people dying? |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-are-we-afraid-to-watch-white-people-dying-20150826-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 13, 2016 |date=August 27, 2015 }}</ref> wrote that the American mainstream media were too selective about rebroadcasting the footage of Parker and Ward's deaths to white audiences but have frequently showed content of many black people being killed. ''Los Angeles Times'' writer [[Mary McNamara]] wrote that not watching the graphic footage to prevent the fulfillment of \"a killer's wish is not just absurd it's agreeing to adopt a murderer's way of thinking.\" She said that people should watch the footage, not for entertainment, but to realize how brutal the murders were.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mary |last=McNamara |date=August 26, 2015 |title=If we watch the Virginia TV shooting is the suspected shooter 'winning'? |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-critics-notebook-virginia-shooting-20150827-53-column.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 15, 2016 }}</ref> ''New York Daily News'' writer Linda Stasi said that media criticism of showing footage contradicted frequent media decisions to publish other violent content.<ref>{{cite web |first=Linda |last=Stasi |date=August 29, 2015 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/stasi-time-focus-evil-not-media-article-1.2341740 |title=It's time to focus on the evil, not the media |website=New York Daily News |accessdate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Virginia State Police ordered BBC journalists to delete the station's copy of the video of Flanagan crashing his car during the police chase before he committed suicide.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kierran |last=Petersen |date=August 26, 2015 |title=Update: Virginia police order BBC journalists to delete footage of suspected shooter's crash |url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-08-26/virginia-police-order-bbc-journalists-delete-footage-suspected-shooters-crash |website=PRI |accessdate=December 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Battling online material ===\nIn a sworn Congressional Testimony in July 2019, Alison's father Andy Parker credited the [[HONR Network]] in assisting him to combat online offensive material and hoaxes spread after the tragedy, saying \"the HONR Network who worked long hours flagging videos so that I was spared. When finding offensive content, HONR volunteers would click the report button below each video and check the appropriate box explaining how the video violates [[YouTube]]'s Community Guidelines. Although hundreds of videos have been taken down due to their diligence, they are often stymied even with an enforceable copyright.\"<ref name=\"senate\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Parker%20Testimony1.pdf|title=Andy Parker Congressional Testimony|last=Parker|first=Andy|date=July 16, 2019|website=US Federal Judiciary Committee|language=en-us|format=PDF|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2019.10.27-051837/https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Parker%20Testimony1.pdf|archive-date=2019-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-sandy-hook-memorial-charities-htmlstory.html|title=Foundations Honor Sandy Hook Victims Six Years Later|last=Ormseth|first=Matthew|date=December 14, 2018|work=courant.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402204355/https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-sandy-hook-memorial-charities-htmlstory.html|archive-date=2019-04-02|publisher=Hartford Courant Media Group}}</ref> He also added \"I have engaged in direct communications with [[Google]] regarding the proliferation of these videos, but while they profess a desire to help, in reality they do nothing... [I met with] Google Director of Global Human Rights regarding specific content and our attempts to have it removed. Their response was \u201cWe\u2019re really trying\u201d. Since that meeting, there has been nothing but silence. Thanks to [[Section 230]], Google has complete immunity and therefore no incentive to respond.\"<ref name=senate /> On February 20, 2020, Andy Parker filed a complaint to the [[Federal Trade Commission]] alleging that YouTube had failed to enforce its own [[Terms of Service]] by keeping certain videos of the shooting on its website.<ref>{{cite web |last=Reichert |first=Corinne |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/youtube-faces-ftc-complaint-after-failing-to-take-down-videos-of-journalists-murder/|title=YouTube faces FTC complaint after failing to take down videos of journalist's murder |publisher=CNET |date=February 20, 2020 |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Virginia}}\n* [[Capital Gazette shooting]]\n* [[Christine Chubbuck]], a television news reporter and the first person to commit suicide on live television in 1974\n* [[Crime in Virginia]]\n* [[R. Budd Dwyer]], the former state treasurer of Pennsylvania who shot himself on live television in 1987\n* [[List of journalists killed in the United States]]\n* [[Workplace aggression]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Alison}}\n[[Category:2015 in American television]]\n[[Category:2015 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:2015 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2015]]\n[[Category:August 2015 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bedford County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Filmed killings]]\n[[Category:Journalists killed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder\u2013suicides in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence against European Americans]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence in the United States]]\n[[Category:Racism in television]]\n[[Category:Workplace violence]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toKMID(link changed toKMID (TV)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murders_of_Alison_Parker_and_Adam_Ward"}
{"title_page": "Coronavirus recession", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Merge to|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|discuss=Talk:Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Proposed merge of Coronavirus recession into Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{globalize|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:DowJones2020crash.png|thumb|Movement of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] between December 2019 and March 2020, showing the all-time high in February, and the crash in February and March during the COVID-19 pandemic]]\n\nThe '''Coronavirus recession''' is an [[economic recession]] which started affecting the [[world economy]] in [[2020]] due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/3/21/21188541/coronavirus-news-recession-economy-unemployment-stock-market-jobs-gdp|title=The coronavirus recession is already here|last=Stewart|first=Emily|date=21 March 2020|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Islam|first=Faisal|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51984470|title=Coronavirus recession not yet a depression|date=20 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6695294/the-coronavirus-recession-has-arrived/|title=The coronavirus recession has arrived|last=Times|first=The Canberra|date=25 March 2020|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> It is one [[socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. While economic data takes time to be collected, many economists agree that the recession is already happening.<ref name=\":0\" /> This has also been supported by findings from [[Purchasing Managers' Index|surveys of purchasing managers]] in the [[United States]], [[Europe]] and [[China]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tokyo|first=Harriet Torry in Washington, Paul Hannon in London and Megumi Fujikawa in|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-could-trigger-global-recession-says-imf-11585046688|title=Coronavirus Triggers Record Drops in U.S., European Business Activity|date=24 March 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/economy/china-services-employment-coronavirus/index.html|title=China's economy could shrink for the first time in decades because of the coronavirus|last=Business|first=Laura He, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The United States currently has almost five times as many unemployment claims as during the previous peak in 1982.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21|title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=2020-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n[[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] managing director, Kristalina Georgieva, on March 24 declared in a statement that the [[global economy]] will contract in 2020 and this \"recession [is] at least as bad as during the global financial crisis or worse.\" Almost 80 countries have asked the IMF for help.<ref>[https://www.afr.com/policy/economy/imf-forecasts-2020-global-recession-recovery-in-2021-20200324-p54d7h IMF forecasts 2020 global recession, recovery in 2021]</ref>\n\nMany countries with large economies, such as Italy and Spain, have enacted [[quarantine]] policies. This has led to the disruption of business activities in many economic sectors.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Developing countries are also forecast to be severely impacted by the coronavirus.<ref>[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3563616 Forecasting the Economic Impact of Coronavirus on Developing Countries.] ''Political Economy - Development: Health eJournal.'' Social Science Research Network. Accessed 30 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==Global stock market crash==\n{{see also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe global [[2020 stock market crash|stock market crash]] began on the 20 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Samuelson |first=Robert J. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/what-crash-2020-means/ |title=What Crash of 2020 Means |date=12 March 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wearden (earlier) |first=Graeme |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live |title=Wall Street and FTSE 100 plunge on worst day since 1987 \u2013 as it happened |date=12 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=12 March 2020 |last2=Jolly |first2=Jasper |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/10/stock-market-crash-2020-everything-you-need-to-kno.aspx |title=Stock Market Crash 2020: Everything You Need to Know |last=Williams |first=Sean |date=10 March 2020 |website=The Motley Fool |language=en |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Global markets into early March became extremely volatile, with large swings occurring in global markets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1748051/dow-industrials-surge-500-points-extending-volatile-streak/? |title=Asian shares rise following stimulus-led surge on Wall St |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |website=MyNorthwest}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-volatile-is-the-coronavirus-stricken-stock-market-after-the-worst-week-since-2008-the-dow-is-now-on-pace-for-its-best-week-since-2011-2020-03-04 |title=Wild stock-market swings are 'emotionally and intellectually wearing' on Wall Street |last=DeCambre |first=Mark |date=7 March 2020 |website=MarketWatch |language=en-US |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 9&nbsp;March, most global markets reported severe contractions, mainly in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and a described [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first1=Laura|last1=He|first2=Clare|last2=Duffy|first3=Julia|last3=Horowitz|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/08/investing/stock-dow-futures-coronavirus/index.html |title=US stocks halted after falling 7%. Global stocks plunge as oil crashes and coronavirus fear spreads |access-date=15 March 2020 |website=CNN}}</ref> This became colloquially known as Black Monday I, and at the time was the worst drop since the [[Great Recession]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/stock-markets-ftse-100-oil-prices-coronavirus-black-monday-a4382156.html |title=Black Monday: Fourth biggest City fall as virus panic hits markets |last=Prynn |first=Jonathon |last2=English |first2=Simon |date=9 March 2020 |website=Evening Standard |language=en |access-date=13 March 2020 |last3=Murphy |first3=Joe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Impact by sector ==\n\n=== Retail sector ===\nShopping centers around the world responded by reducing hours or closing down temporarily in response. As of 18 March 2020, the footfall to shopping centers fell by up-to 30%, with significant impact in every continent.<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.aislelabs.com/blog/2020/03/23/how-shopping-centres-responding-coronavirus/  |title=How Shopping Centres Globally are Responding to Coronavirus by Aislelabs|author=Inc, Aislelabs|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> [[Simon Property Group]] became the first major US-based mall operator to close all centers on the 18th March, with government mandated closures in UAE, Italy, Germany, Spain, Brazil and Austria as of 23 March.\n\n===Transportation sector===\n{{generalize|section|date=March 2020}}\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation}}\n[[File:A nearly empty flight from PEK to LAX amid the COVID-19 pandemic 1.jpg|thumb|A nearly empty flight from [[Beijing]] to [[Los Angeles]] during the pandemic]]\n\nThe pandemic has had a significant impact on aviation industry due to [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the resulting travel restrictions]] as well as slump in demand among travelers. Significant reductions in passenger numbers has resulted in planes flying empty between airports and the cancellation of flights.\n\n=== Restaurant sector ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\nThe 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic has impacted the restaurant business. In the beginning of March 2020, some major cities in the US announced that bars and restaurants would be closed to sit-down diners and limited to [[Food delivery|takeout orders and delivery]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319091659/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some employees were fired, and more employees lacked [[sick leave]] in the sector compared to similar sectors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus exposes sick leave gap for retail, restaurant workers |url=https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/ |website=Press Enterprise |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318153437/https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nber.org/papers/w26832.pdf Sick leave] ''[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]''</ref>\n\n== Impact by country ==\n=== Australia ===\nUp to a million people have been laid off due to effects of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henriques-Gomes|first=Luke|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/24/newly-unemployed-australians-queue-at-centrelink-offices-as-mygov-website-crashes-again|title=Newly unemployed Australians queue at Centrelink offices as MyGov website crashes again|date=24 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Over 280,000 individuals applied for unemployment support at the peak day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/surge-in-demand-280-000-ask-centrelink-for-help-in-one-day-20200325-p54dwn.html|title='Surge in demand': 280,000 ask Centrelink for help in one day|last=Bonyhady|first=Nick|date=2020-03-25|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHousing prices in Australia could drop up to 20% as a result of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farrer|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/20/australian-housing-market-will-hit-the-wall-in-coronavirus-recession-experts-say|title=Australian housing market will hit the wall in coronavirus recession, experts say|date=19 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\n\nMinister of Finance of [[Hesse]] [[Thomas Sch\u00e4fer]] was found dead on 28 March 2020. Sch\u00e4fer left a suicide note, where he mentions the \"hopeless\" economic situation in the country as one of the reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tichyseinblick.de/daili-es-sentials/zum-tod-des-hessischen-finanzministers-thomas-schaefer/|title=Zum Tod des hessischen Finanzministers Thomas Sch\u00e4fer|date=2020-03-29|website=Tichys Einblick|language=de}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\nA new record of unemployment claims was made, with 3.3 million claims made in the week ending on 21 March, with the previous record being 700,000 from 1982.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21 |title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew |date=2020-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Restaurant patronage has fallen sharply across the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business|last=Molla|first=Rani |date=16 March 2020|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> and major airlines are reducing their operations on a large scale.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/airline-news/2020/03/18/coronavirus-travel-fallout-united-jetblue-allegiant-slash-flights/2863432001/ |title=American Airlines cuts 55,000 flights, parks 450 planes amid coronavirus: 'Fight of our lives'|last=Gilbertson|first=Dawn |website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three car manufacturers]] have all halted production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/business/gm-ford-automakers-us-shut-down/index.html |title=GM, Ford and other automakers to halt production in the US|last=Business|first=Peter Valdes-Dapena and Vanessa Yurkevich, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[yield curve#Inverted yield curve|yield curve inverted]] in  2019, usually indicative of a forthcoming recession.<ref>{{cite web |title=A closely followed recession indicator is flashing its most worrying sign in 12 years {{!}} Markets Insider |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644 |website=markets.businessinsider.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190930224654/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644 |archivedate=September 30, 2019 |date=May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-09/u-s-yield-curve-inverts-for-the-first-time-since-march |website=www.bloomberg.com |date=May 2019}}</ref> The [[St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index]] increased sharply from below zero<!--Feb 21--> to 5.8<!--March 20--> during March 2020.<ref name=STLFSI2blog>{{cite web |title=The St. Louis Fed\u2019s Financial Stress Index, Version 2.0 {{!}} FRED Blog |url=https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327224916/https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/ |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live |quote=The revised STLFSI, however, has increased sharply\u2014reminiscent of the worst of the financial market turmoil during the Great Recession in 2008-2009\u2014registering a value close to 5.8.}}</ref><ref name=STLFSI2>{{cite web |title=St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index (STLFSI2) |url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2 |website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222839/https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2 |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019-nCoV}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in economics]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Merge to|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|discuss=Talk:Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Proposed merge of Coronavirus recession into Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{globalize|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:DowJones2020crash.png|thumb|Movement of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] between December 2019 and March 2020, showing the all-time high in February, and the crash in February and March during the COVID-19 pandemic]] \n\nThe '''Coronavirus recession''' is an [[economic recession]] which started affecting the [[world economy]] in [[2020]] due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/3/21/21188541/coronavirus-news-recession-economy-unemployment-stock-market-jobs-gdp|title=The coronavirus recession is already here|last=Stewart|first=Emily|date=21 March 2020|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Islam|first=Faisal|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51984470|title=Coronavirus recession not yet a depression|date=20 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6695294/the-coronavirus-recession-has-arrived/|title=The coronavirus recession has arrived|last=Times|first=The Canberra|date=25 March 2020|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> It is one [[socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. While economic data takes time to be collected, many economists agree that the recession is already happening.<ref name=\":0\" /> This has also been supported by findings from [[Purchasing Managers' Index|surveys of purchasing managers]] in the [[United States]], [[Europe]] and [[China]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tokyo|first=Harriet Torry in Washington, Paul Hannon in London and Megumi Fujikawa in|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-could-trigger-global-recession-says-imf-11585046688|title=Coronavirus Triggers Record Drops in U.S., European Business Activity|date=24 March 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/economy/china-services-employment-coronavirus/index.html|title=China's economy could shrink for the first time in decades because of the coronavirus|last=Business|first=Laura He, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The United States currently has almost five times as many unemployment claims as during the previous peak in 1982.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21|title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=2020-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n[[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] managing director, Kristalina Georgieva, on March 24 declared in a statement that the [[global economy]] will contract in 2020 and this \"recession [is] at least as bad as during the global financial crisis or worse.\" Almost 80 countries have asked the IMF for help.<ref>[https://www.afr.com/policy/economy/imf-forecasts-2020-global-recession-recovery-in-2021-20200324-p54d7h IMF forecasts 2020 global recession, recovery in 2021]</ref>\n\nMany countries with large economies, such as Italy and Spain, have enacted [[Quarantine|quarantine]] policies. This has led to the disruption of business activities in many economic sectors.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Developing countries are also forecast to be severely impacted by the coronavirus.<ref>[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3563616 Forecasting the Economic Impact of Coronavirus on Developing Countries.] ''Political Economy - Development: Health eJournal.'' Social Science Research Network. Accessed 30 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==Global stock market crash==\n{{see also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe global [[2020 stock market crash|stock market crash]] began on the 20 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Samuelson |first=Robert J. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/what-crash-2020-means/ |title=What Crash of 2020 Means |date=12 March 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wearden (earlier) |first=Graeme |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live |title=Wall Street and FTSE 100 plunge on worst day since 1987 \u2013 as it happened |date=12 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=12 March 2020 |last2=Jolly |first2=Jasper |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/10/stock-market-crash-2020-everything-you-need-to-kno.aspx |title=Stock Market Crash 2020: Everything You Need to Know |last=Williams |first=Sean |date=10 March 2020 |website=The Motley Fool |language=en |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Global markets into early March became extremely volatile, with large swings occurring in global markets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1748051/dow-industrials-surge-500-points-extending-volatile-streak/? |title=Asian shares rise following stimulus-led surge on Wall St |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |website=MyNorthwest}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-volatile-is-the-coronavirus-stricken-stock-market-after-the-worst-week-since-2008-the-dow-is-now-on-pace-for-its-best-week-since-2011-2020-03-04 |title=Wild stock-market swings are 'emotionally and intellectually wearing' on Wall Street |last=DeCambre |first=Mark |date=7 March 2020 |website=MarketWatch |language=en-US |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 9&nbsp;March, most global markets reported severe contractions, mainly in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and a described [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first1=Laura|last1=He|first2=Clare|last2=Duffy|first3=Julia|last3=Horowitz|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/08/investing/stock-dow-futures-coronavirus/index.html |title=US stocks halted after falling 7%. Global stocks plunge as oil crashes and coronavirus fear spreads |access-date=15 March 2020 |website=CNN}}</ref> This became colloquially known as Black Monday I, and at the time was the worst drop since the [[Great Recession]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/stock-markets-ftse-100-oil-prices-coronavirus-black-monday-a4382156.html |title=Black Monday: Fourth biggest City fall as virus panic hits markets |last=Prynn |first=Jonathon |last2=English |first2=Simon |date=9 March 2020 |website=Evening Standard |language=en |access-date=13 March 2020 |last3=Murphy |first3=Joe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Impact by sector ==\n\n=== Retail sector ===\nShopping centers around the world responded by reducing hours or closing down temporarily in response. As of 18 March 2020, the footfall to shopping centers fell by up-to 30%, with significant impact in every continent.<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.aislelabs.com/blog/2020/03/23/how-shopping-centres-responding-coronavirus/  |title=How Shopping Centres Globally are Responding to Coronavirus by Aislelabs|author=Inc, Aislelabs|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> [[Simon Property Group]] became the first major US-based mall operator to close all centers on the 18th March, with government mandated closures in UAE, Italy, Germany, Spain, Brazil and Austria as of 23rd March.\n\n===Transportation sector===\n{{generalise|section|date=March 2020}}\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation}}\n[[File:A nearly empty flight from PEK to LAX amid the COVID-19 pandemic 1.jpg|thumb|A nearly empty flight from [[Beijing]] to [[Los Angeles]] during the pandemic]]\n\nThe pandemic has had a significant impact on aviation industry due to [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the resulting travel restrictions]] as well as slump in demand among travelers. Significant reductions in passenger numbers has resulted in planes flying empty between airports and the cancellation of flights.\n\n=== Restaurant sector ===\n{{Main articles|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\nThe 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic has impacted the restaurant business. In the beginning of March 2020, some major cities in the US announced that bars and restaurants would be closed to sit-down diners and limited to [[Food delivery|takeout orders and delivery]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319091659/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some employees were fired, and more employees lacked [[sick leave]] in the sector compared to similar sectors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus exposes sick leave gap for retail, restaurant workers |url=https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/ |website=Press Enterprise |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318153437/https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nber.org/papers/w26832.pdf Sick leave] ''[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]''</ref>\n\n== Impact by country ==\n=== Australia ===\nUp to a million people have been laid off due to effects of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henriques-Gomes|first=Luke|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/24/newly-unemployed-australians-queue-at-centrelink-offices-as-mygov-website-crashes-again|title=Newly unemployed Australians queue at Centrelink offices as MyGov website crashes again|date=24 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Over 280,000 individuals applied for unemployment support at the peak day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/surge-in-demand-280-000-ask-centrelink-for-help-in-one-day-20200325-p54dwn.html|title='Surge in demand': 280,000 ask Centrelink for help in one day|last=Bonyhady|first=Nick|date=2020-03-25|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHousing prices in Australia could drop up to 20% as a result of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farrer|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/20/australian-housing-market-will-hit-the-wall-in-coronavirus-recession-experts-say|title=Australian housing market will hit the wall in coronavirus recession, experts say|date=19 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\n\nMinister of Finance of [[Hesse]] [[Thomas Sch\u00e4fer]] was found dead on 28 March 2020. Sch\u00e4fer left a suicide note, where he mentions the \"hopeless\" economic situation in the country as one of the reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tichyseinblick.de/daili-es-sentials/zum-tod-des-hessischen-finanzministers-thomas-schaefer/|title=Zum Tod des hessischen Finanzministers Thomas Sch\u00e4fer|date=2020-03-29|website=Tichys Einblick|language=de}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\nA new record of unemployment claims was made, with 3.3 million claims made in the week ending on 21 March, with the previous record being 700,000 from 1982.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21 |title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew |date=2020-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Restaurant patronage has fallen sharply across the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business|last=Molla|first=Rani |date=16 March 2020|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> and major airlines are reducing their operations on a large scale.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/airline-news/2020/03/18/coronavirus-travel-fallout-united-jetblue-allegiant-slash-flights/2863432001/ |title=American Airlines cuts 55,000 flights, parks 450 planes amid coronavirus: 'Fight of our lives'|last=Gilbertson|first=Dawn |website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three car manufacturers]] have all halted production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/business/gm-ford-automakers-us-shut-down/index.html |title=GM, Ford and other automakers to halt production in the US|last=Business|first=Peter Valdes-Dapena and Vanessa Yurkevich, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[yield curve#Inverted yield curve|yield curve inverted]] in  2019, usually indicative of a forthcoming recession.<ref>{{cite web |title=A closely followed recession indicator is flashing its most worrying sign in 12 years {{!}} Markets Insider |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644 |website=markets.businessinsider.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190930224654/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644 |archivedate=September 30, 2019 |date=May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-09/u-s-yield-curve-inverts-for-the-first-time-since-march |website=www.bloomberg.com |date=May 2019}}</ref> The [[St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index]] increased sharply from below zero<!--Feb 21--> to 5.8<!--March 20--> during March 2020.<ref name=STLFSI2blog>{{cite web |title=The St. Louis Fed\u2019s Financial Stress Index, Version 2.0 {{!}} FRED Blog |url=https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327224916/https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/ |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live |quote=The revised STLFSI, however, has increased sharply\u2014reminiscent of the worst of the financial market turmoil during the Great Recession in 2008-2009\u2014registering a value close to 5.8.}}</ref><ref name=STLFSI2>{{cite web |title=St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index (STLFSI2) |url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2 |website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222839/https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2 |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019-nCoV}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in economics]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n", "name_user": "DePiep", "label": "safe", "comment": "WP COVID-19: check for MOS and typo's.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_recession"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States Senate election in Iowa", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 United States Senate election in Iowa\n| country            = Iowa\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes \n| previous_election  = 2014 United States Senate election in Iowa\n| previous_year      = 2014\n| next_election      = 2026 United States Senate election in Iowa\n| next_year          = 2026\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n| image1             = [[File:Joni Ernst official portrait (cropped).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1           = [[Joni Ernst]]\n| party1             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = \n| party2             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| map_image          = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. Senator\n| before_election    = [[Joni Ernst]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     = \n| after_party        = \n}}\n{{ElectionsIA}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States Senate election in Iowa''' will be held on November 3, 2020, to elect a member of the [[United States Senate]] to represent the [[Iowa|State of Iowa]], concurrently with the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], as well as [[2020 United States Senate elections|other elections]] to the United States Senate in other states and [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections|elections]] to the [[United States House of Representatives]] and various [[2020 United States elections|state and local elections]]. The primary is scheduled for June 2.<ref>{{cite web |title=United States Senate election in Iowa, 2020 (June 2 Democratic primary) |url=https://ballotpedia.org/United_States_Senate_election_in_Iowa,_2020_(June_2_Democratic_primary) |website=ballotpedia.org |accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n*[[Joni Ernst]], incumbent U.S. Senator<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cohen|first1=Zach C.|title=How 2014's Outsiders Became 2020's Insiders|url=https://www.nationaljournal.com/s/675089/how-2014s-outsiders-became-2020s-insiders|publisher=National Journal|date=December 5, 2018|accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/420411-iowas-ernst-will-run-for-reelection-in-2020|title=Iowa's Ernst will run for reelection in 2020|last=Axelrod|first=Tal|date=2018-12-08|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.politics1.com/ia.htm|title=Politics1 - Online Guide to Iowa Politics|last=Gunzburger|first=Ron|website=politics1.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-31}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{Endorsements box\n| title= Joni Ernst\n|list=\n;Organizations\n* [[Maggie's List]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://maggieslist.org/candidates/2020-candidates|title=2020 Candidates|website=maggieslist.org}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box  candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Joni Ernst]] (incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.00%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Democratic primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n*[[Michael T. Franken]], retired U.S. Navy admiral and former aide to U.S. Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pfannenstiel|first1=Brianne|title=Retired Navy Admiral Michael Franken to run for U.S. Senate, challenge Joni Ernst|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/26/michael-franken-challenges-joni-ernst-iowa-us-senate-navy-admiral-democratic-primary-candidates/2099469001/|publisher=Des Moines Register|date=August 26, 2019|accessd