{"title_page": "Spoilage", "text_new": "{{Wiktionary|spoilage|spoiled|spoiling}}\n'''Spoilage''', '''spoiling''' or (making something) '''spoiled''' may refer to:\n* [[Spoiled child]], a derogatory term aimed at children who exhibit behavioral problems from being overindulged by their parents.\n* A ''spoiled'' high-schooler known as '''''JoJo Siwa''''' is a ''spoiled'' [[brat]] who believes that her bow company makes her the most famous girl on Earth. This may be because she is '''''spoiled'''''.\n*[[Decomposition]], the process by which organic substances are broken down into simpler matter.\n** [[Food spoilage]], the process in which food deteriorates to the point in which it is not edible to humans or its quality of edibility becomes reduced\n* ''Spoiling'' of a [[MRI_sequence#Gradient_echo|gradient echo magnetic resonance sequence]]\n* [[Spoiled (film)|''Spoiled'' (film)]], a 2011 documentary film\n* [[Spoiled (play)|''Spoiled'' (play)]], a television and stage play\n* [[Spoiled (song)|\"Spoiled\" (song)]], a 2005 song by Joss Stone\n*\"Spoiled\", a song by Basement from their 2012 album ''[[Colourmeinkindness]]''\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Decay (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Decomposition (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Spoil (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "text_old": "{{Wiktionary|spoilage|spoiled|spoiling}}\n'''Spoilage''', '''spoiling''' or (making something) '''spoiled''' may refer to:\n* [[Spoiled child]], a derogatory term aimed at children who exhibit behavioral problems from being overindulged by their parents.\n*[[Decomposition]], the process by which organic substances are broken down into simpler matter.\n** [[Food spoilage]], the process in which food deteriorates to the point in which it is not edible to humans or its quality of edibility becomes reduced\n* ''Spoiling'' of a [[MRI_sequence#Gradient_echo|gradient echo magnetic resonance sequence]]\n* [[Spoiled (film)|''Spoiled'' (film)]], a 2011 documentary film\n* [[Spoiled (play)|''Spoiled'' (play)]], a television and stage play\n* [[Spoiled (song)|\"Spoiled\" (song)]], a 2005 song by Joss Stone\n*\"Spoiled\", a song by Basement from their 2012 album ''[[Colourmeinkindness]]''\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Decay (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Decomposition (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Spoil (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "2601:84:8902:8210:4c07:c45f:2ca1:1c6b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed grammar)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spoilage"}
{"title_page": "Vasant (magazine)", "text_new": "{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Vasant\n| image_file      = \n| image_size      =  \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = {{plainlist|\n* [[Anandshankar Dhruv]]\n* [[Ramanbhai Neelkanth]] (1912\u20131924)\n}}\n| editor_title    = Editor(s)\n| category        = literature, religion, philosophy, ethics, politics, education, economics, sociology, science\n| frequency       = Monthly\n| founder         = Anandshankar Dhruv\n| founded         = 1902\n| firstdate       = {{Start date and age|1902}}\n| finaldate       = {{End date|1939}}\n| finalnumber     = \n| country         = [[British Raj|British India]]\n| based           = \n| language        = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n}}\n\n'''''Vasant''''' was a [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]-language magazine founded and edited by [[Anandshankar Dhruv]], which ran from 1902 to 1939. The magazine played a key role in the development of [[Gujarati literature|Gujarati prose writing]], and is considered to hold a significant place in the tradition of [[Media in Gujarati language|Gujarati literary magazines]].\n\n==History==\nDhruv edited ''[[Sudarshan (magazine)|Sudarshan]]'', a magazine founded by his close friend [[Manilal Dwivedi]], for about four years. In 1902, he started his own monthly magazine, ''Vasant''.<ref name=\"Mehta2912\">{{Cite book|title=S\u0101hityika S\u0101mayiko : Parampar\u0101 ane Prabh\u0101va|publisher=Rannade Prakashan|isbn=978-93-82456-01-8|editor-last=Mehta|editor-first=Hasit|edition=1st|location=Ahmedabad|date=May 2012|pages=70\u201371|language=gu|script-title=gu:\u0ab8\u0abe\u0ab9\u0abf\u0aa4\u0acd\u0aaf\u0abf\u0a95 \u0ab8\u0abe\u0aae\u0aaf\u0abf\u0a95\u0acb : \u0aaa\u0ab0\u0a82\u0aaa\u0ab0\u0abe \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aad\u0abe\u0ab5|trans-title=Literary Magazines : Tradition and Influence|oclc=824686453}}</ref> Dhruv stated the aim of magazine in the first issue:\n\n{{quote|If we look back into the history of last fifty years, we will notice that the way we think and the way we behave/live have undergone a change. Some old problems are resolved, and some are being discussed from a different viewpoint. Some new problems have come into existence and a few more are likely to. In this situation, Gujarat needs a monthly journal which can reflect the time we live in and can also help in the progress of our life. We will satisfy if this monthly can fulfill this need. This is, in fact, the goal of this new journal.|Anandshankar Dhruv, 1902<ref name=\"Shah2004\">{{Cite encyclopedia|last=Shah|first=Priti|title=\u0ab5\u0ab8\u0a82\u0aa4|encyclopedia=[[Gujarati Vishwakosh]]|volume=XIX|editor-last=Thakar|editor-first=Dhirubhai|editor-link=Dhirubhai Thaker|publisher=Gujarat Vishwakosh Trust|year=2004|edition=1st|oclc=552367205|location=Ahmedabad|pages=566\u2013567|language=gu}}</ref>{{efn|English translation. Original statement in Gujarati:<br/>\n\"\u0a86\u0aaa\u0aa3\u0acb \u0a9b\u0ac7\u0ab2\u0acd\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a82 \u0aaa\u0a9a\u0abe\u0ab8 \u0ab5\u0ab0\u0acd\u0ab7\u0acb\u0aa8\u0acb \u0a88\u0aa4\u0abf\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab8 \u0a85\u0ab5\u0ab2\u0acb\u0a95\u0ac0\u0ab6\u0ac1\u0a82 \u0aa4\u0acb \u0a9c\u0aa3\u0abe\u0ab6\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0ac7 \u0a8f \u0aa6\u0ab0\u0aae\u0abf\u0aaf\u0abe\u0aa8 \u0a86\u0aaa\u0aa3\u0abe \u0a86\u0a9a\u0abe\u0ab0\u0ab5\u0abf\u0a9a\u0abe\u0ab0 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0ab0\u0acd\u0aa4\u0ab5\u0acd\u0aaf\u0aad\u0abe\u0ab5\u0aa8\u0abe\u0aa8\u0abe \u0ab8\u0acd\u0ab5\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0aaa\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7\u0a95 \u0aab\u0ac7\u0ab0\u0aab\u0abe\u0ab0\u0acb \u0aa5\u0a88 \u0a97\u0aaf\u0abe \u0a9b\u0ac7. \u0a95\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a95 \u0a9c\u0ac2\u0aa8\u0abe \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ab6\u0acd\u0aa8\u0acb \u0a86\u0a9c\u0ac7 \u0aaa\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0a97\u0aaf\u0abe \u0a9b\u0ac7 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a95 \u0aa8\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0aa8 \u0aaa\u0aa6\u0acd\u0aa7\u0aa4\u0abf\u0a8f \u0a9a\u0ab0\u0acd\u0a9a\u0abe\u0ab5\u0abe \u0ab2\u0abe\u0a97\u0acd\u0aaf\u0abe \u0a9b\u0ac7. \u0a95\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a95 \u0aa8\u0ab5\u0abe \u0a89\u0aa4\u0acd\u0aaa\u0aa8\u0acd\u0aa8 \u0aa5\u0aaf\u0abe \u0a9b\u0ac7 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a95 \u0aa5\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0ab6\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0a86\u0aa4\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82 \u0a9b\u0ac7. \u0a86\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0acd\u0aa5\u0abf\u0aa4\u0abf\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82, \u0ab8\u0aae\u0aaf\u0aa8\u0ac1\u0a82 \u0aaf\u0acb\u0a97\u0acd\u0aaf \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aa4\u0abf\u0aac\u0abf\u0a82\u0aac \u0a9d\u0ac0\u0ab2\u0ac7 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aa4\u0ac7\u0aa8\u0abe \u0a9c\u0ac0\u0ab5\u0aa8\u0ab5\u0abf\u0a95\u0abe\u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82 \u0a95\u0abe\u0a82\u0a88\u0a95 \u0aaa\u0aa3 \u0ab8\u0ab9\u0abe\u0aaf\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0aaa \u0aa5\u0abe\u0aaf \u0a8f\u0ab5\u0abe \u0a8f\u0a95 \u0aae\u0abe\u0ab8\u0abf\u0a95\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aac\u0ab9\u0ac1 \u0a9c\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0ab0 \u0a9b\u0ac7. \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a8f \u0a9c\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0ab0 \u0aa5\u0acb\u0aa1\u0ac0\u0a98\u0aa3\u0ac0 \u0aaa\u0aa3 \u0a95\u0a82\u0a88\u0a95 \u0ab8\u0a82\u0aa4\u0acb\u0ab7\u0a95\u0abe\u0ab0\u0a95 \u0ab0\u0ac0\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0aaa\u0ac2\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0aaa\u0abe\u0aa1\u0ac0 \u0ab6\u0a95\u0abe\u0aaf \u0aa4\u0acb \u0aa0\u0ac0\u0a95, \u0a8f \u0a86 \u0aa8\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0aa8 \u0a89\u0aaa\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aae\u0aa8\u0acb \u0a8f\u0a95 \u0a89\u0aa6\u0acd\u0aa6\u0ac7\u0ab6 \u0a9b\u0ac7.\"}}}}\n\nFrom 1912 to 1924, [[Ramanbhai Neelkanth]] edited the magazine, and from 1925, Dhruv again took over its editorship. Due to the irregular publication, the magazine became quarterly in 1936. It was disestablished in 1939.<ref name=\"Shah2004\"/>\n\n==Contents==\nThe magazine used to discuss wide range of topics including religion, philosophy, poetry, ethics, politics, education, economics, sociology, science, research and various aspects of literature and life.<ref name=\"Commemoration Volume\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Parikh|editor1-first=Rasiklal C.|editor1-link=Rasiklal Parikh|editor2-last=Trivedi|editor2-first=Ratilal M.|editor3-last=Joshi|editor3-first=Umashankar|editor3-link=Umashankar Joshi|title=Acharya Dhruva Smaraka Grantha [Acharya Dhruva Commemoration Volume]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H5MvAQAAMAAJ|year=1946|publisher=[[Gujarat Vidhya Sabha]]|publication-place=Ahmedabad|pages=10\u201311|oclc=769701345}}</ref> From the first issue of the magazine, a series of article written by [[Uttamlal Trivedi]] started appearing under the title ''Saraswatichandra ane Aapno Grihasansar'', based on [[Govardhanram Tripathi]]'s novel ''[[Saraswatichandra (novel)|Saraswatichandra]]''. After the death of Govardhanram Tripathi in January 1907, Dhruv published the special volume of the magazine dedicated to Tripathi in March 1907.<ref name=\"Shah2004\"/>\n\nThe regular contributors to the magazine were [[Manishankar Bhatt]] 'Kant', [[Nhanalal]], [[Narayan Hemchandra]], [[Ramanbhai Neelkanth]], [[Vishnuprasad Trivedi]], [[Krishnalal Jhaveri]], [[Balwantray Thakore]], and [[Narsinhrao Divetia]] etc.<ref name=\"Shah2004\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nConsidered to have a significant place in the tradition of Gujarati literary magazines, the magazine played a key-role in the development of Gujarati prose writing.<ref name=\"Shah2004\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Gujarati-language magazines]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author|search=Vasant Ank}}\n\n[[Category:1902 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:1939 disestablishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:Gujarati-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Indian monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1902]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1939]]\n[[Category:Media in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Vasant\n| image_file      = \n| image_size      =  \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = {{plainlist|\n* [[Anandshankar Dhruv]]\n* [[Ramanbhai Neelkanth]] (1912\u20131924)\n}}\n| editor_title    = Editor(s)\n| category        = literature, religion, philosophy, ethics, politics, education, economics, sociology, science\n| frequency       = Monthly\n| founder         = Anandshankar Dhruv\n| founded         = 1902\n| firstdate       = {{Start date and age|1902}}\n| finaldate       = {{End date|1939}}\n| finalnumber     = \n| country         = [[British Raj|British India]]\n| based           = \n| language        = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n}}\n\n'''''Vasant''''' was a [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]-language magazine founded and edited by [[Anandshankar Dhruv]], which ran from 1902 to 1939. The magazine played a key role in the development of [[Gujarati literature|Gujarati prose writing]], and is considered to hold a significant place in the tradition of [[Media in Gujarati language|Gujarati literary magazines]].\n\n==History==\nDhruv edited ''[[Sudarshan (magazine)|Sudarshan]]'', a magazine founded by his close friend [[Manilal Dwivedi]], for about four years. In 1902, he started his own monthly magazine, ''Vasant''.<ref name=\"Mehta2912\">{{Cite book|title=S\u0101hityika S\u0101mayiko : Parampar\u0101 ane Prabh\u0101va|publisher=Rannade Prakashan|isbn=978-93-82456-01-8|editor-last=Mehta|editor-first=Hasit|edition=1st|location=Ahmedabad|date=May 2012|pages=70\u201371|language=gu|script-title=gu:\u0ab8\u0abe\u0ab9\u0abf\u0aa4\u0acd\u0aaf\u0abf\u0a95 \u0ab8\u0abe\u0aae\u0aaf\u0abf\u0a95\u0acb : \u0aaa\u0ab0\u0a82\u0aaa\u0ab0\u0abe \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aad\u0abe\u0ab5|trans-title=Literary Magazines : Tradition and Influence|oclc=824686453}}</ref> Dhruv stated the aim of magazine in the first issue:\n\n{{quote|If we look back into the history of last fifty years, we will notice that the way we think and the way we behave/live have undergone a change. Some old problems are resolved, and some are being discussed from a different viewpoint. Some new problems have come into existence and a few more are likely to. In this situation, Gujarat needs a monthly journal which can reflect the time we live in and can also help in the progress of our life. We will satisfy if this monthly can fulfill this need. This is, in fact, the goal of this new journal.|Anandshankar Dhruv, 1902<ref name=\"Shah2004\">{{Cite encyclopedia|last=Shah|first=Priti|title=\u0ab5\u0ab8\u0a82\u0aa4|encyclopedia=[[Gujarati Vishwakosh]]|volume=XIX|editor-last=Thakar|editor-first=Dhirubhai|editor-link=Dhirubhai Thaker|publisher=Gujarat Vishwakosh Trust|year=2004|edition=1st|oclc=552367205|location=Ahmedabad|pages=566\u2013567|language=gu}}</ref>{{efn|English translation. Original statement:<br/>\n\"\u0a86\u0aaa\u0aa3\u0acb \u0a9b\u0ac7\u0ab2\u0acd\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a82 \u0aaa\u0a9a\u0abe\u0ab8 \u0ab5\u0ab0\u0acd\u0ab7\u0acb\u0aa8\u0acb \u0a88\u0aa4\u0abf\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab8 \u0a85\u0ab5\u0ab2\u0acb\u0a95\u0ac0\u0ab6\u0ac1\u0a82 \u0aa4\u0acb \u0a9c\u0aa3\u0abe\u0ab6\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0ac7 \u0a8f \u0aa6\u0ab0\u0aae\u0abf\u0aaf\u0abe\u0aa8 \u0a86\u0aaa\u0aa3\u0abe \u0a86\u0a9a\u0abe\u0ab0\u0ab5\u0abf\u0a9a\u0abe\u0ab0 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0ab0\u0acd\u0aa4\u0ab5\u0acd\u0aaf\u0aad\u0abe\u0ab5\u0aa8\u0abe\u0aa8\u0abe \u0ab8\u0acd\u0ab5\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0aaa\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7\u0a95 \u0aab\u0ac7\u0ab0\u0aab\u0abe\u0ab0\u0acb \u0aa5\u0a88 \u0a97\u0aaf\u0abe \u0a9b\u0ac7. \u0a95\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a95 \u0a9c\u0ac2\u0aa8\u0abe \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ab6\u0acd\u0aa8\u0acb \u0a86\u0a9c\u0ac7 \u0aaa\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0a97\u0aaf\u0abe \u0a9b\u0ac7 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a95 \u0aa8\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0aa8 \u0aaa\u0aa6\u0acd\u0aa7\u0aa4\u0abf\u0a8f \u0a9a\u0ab0\u0acd\u0a9a\u0abe\u0ab5\u0abe \u0ab2\u0abe\u0a97\u0acd\u0aaf\u0abe \u0a9b\u0ac7. \u0a95\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a95 \u0aa8\u0ab5\u0abe \u0a89\u0aa4\u0acd\u0aaa\u0aa8\u0acd\u0aa8 \u0aa5\u0aaf\u0abe \u0a9b\u0ac7 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a95\u0ac7\u0a9f\u0ab2\u0abe\u0a95 \u0aa5\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0ab6\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0a86\u0aa4\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82 \u0a9b\u0ac7. \u0a86\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0acd\u0aa5\u0abf\u0aa4\u0abf\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82, \u0ab8\u0aae\u0aaf\u0aa8\u0ac1\u0a82 \u0aaf\u0acb\u0a97\u0acd\u0aaf \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aa4\u0abf\u0aac\u0abf\u0a82\u0aac \u0a9d\u0ac0\u0ab2\u0ac7 \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aa4\u0ac7\u0aa8\u0abe \u0a9c\u0ac0\u0ab5\u0aa8\u0ab5\u0abf\u0a95\u0abe\u0ab8\u0aae\u0abe\u0a82 \u0a95\u0abe\u0a82\u0a88\u0a95 \u0aaa\u0aa3 \u0ab8\u0ab9\u0abe\u0aaf\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0aaa \u0aa5\u0abe\u0aaf \u0a8f\u0ab5\u0abe \u0a8f\u0a95 \u0aae\u0abe\u0ab8\u0abf\u0a95\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0aac\u0ab9\u0ac1 \u0a9c\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0ab0 \u0a9b\u0ac7. \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a8f \u0a9c\u0ab0\u0ac2\u0ab0 \u0aa5\u0acb\u0aa1\u0ac0\u0a98\u0aa3\u0ac0 \u0aaa\u0aa3 \u0a95\u0a82\u0a88\u0a95 \u0ab8\u0a82\u0aa4\u0acb\u0ab7\u0a95\u0abe\u0ab0\u0a95 \u0ab0\u0ac0\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0aaa\u0ac2\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0aaa\u0abe\u0aa1\u0ac0 \u0ab6\u0a95\u0abe\u0aaf \u0aa4\u0acb \u0aa0\u0ac0\u0a95, \u0a8f \u0a86 \u0aa8\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0aa8 \u0a89\u0aaa\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab0\u0aae\u0aa8\u0acb \u0a8f\u0a95 \u0a89\u0aa6\u0acd\u0aa6\u0ac7\u0ab6 \u0a9b\u0ac7.\"}}}}\n\nFrom 1912 to 1924, [[Ramanbhai Neelkanth]] edited the magazine, and from 1925, Dhruv again took over its editorship. Due to the irregular publication, the magazine became quarterly in 1936. It was disestablished in 1939.<ref name=\"Shah2004\"/>\n\n==Contents==\nThe magazine used to discuss wide range of topics including religion, philosophy, poetry, ethics, politics, education, economics, sociology, science, research and various aspects of literature and life.<ref name=\"Commemoration Volume\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Parikh|editor1-first=Rasiklal C.|editor1-link=Rasiklal Parikh|editor2-last=Trivedi|editor2-first=Ratilal M.|editor3-last=Joshi|editor3-first=Umashankar|editor3-link=Umashankar Joshi|title=Acharya Dhruva Smaraka Grantha [Acharya Dhruva Commemoration Volume]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H5MvAQAAMAAJ|year=1946|publisher=[[Gujarat Vidhya Sabha]]|publication-place=Ahmedabad|pages=10\u201311|oclc=769701345}}</ref> From the first issue of the magazine, a series of article written by [[Uttamlal Trivedi]] started appearing under the title ''Saraswatichandra ane Aapno Grihasansar'', based on [[Govardhanram Tripathi]]'s novel ''[[Saraswatichandra (novel)|Saraswatichandra]]''. After the death of Govardhanram Tripathi in January 1907, Dhruv published the special volume of the magazine dedicated to Tripathi in March 1907.<ref name=\"Shah2004\"/>\n\nThe regular contributors to the magazine were [[Manishankar Bhatt]] 'Kant', [[Nhanalal]], [[Narayan Hemchandra]], [[Ramanbhai Neelkanth]], [[Vishnuprasad Trivedi]], [[Krishnalal Jhaveri]], [[Balwantray Thakore]], and [[Narsinhrao Divetia]] etc.<ref name=\"Shah2004\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nConsidered to have a significant place in the tradition of Gujarati literary magazines, the magazine played a key-role in the development of Gujarati prose writing.<ref name=\"Shah2004\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Gujarati-language magazines]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author|search=Vasant Ank}}\n\n[[Category:1902 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:1939 disestablishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:Gujarati-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Indian monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1902]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1939]]\n[[Category:Media in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of India]]\n", "name_user": "FiveFaintFootprints", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce - further tweak", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vasant_(magazine)"}
